o Raiku]]\n** ''Tatakae! Ry\u014dzanpaku Shij\u014d Saiky\u014d no Deshi'' by Shun Matsuena\n* 2000\n**''Ch\u014d Ikusei Shinwa Pagunasu'' by Ry\u014d \u014ckuma\n* 2001\n**''HEAT WAVE'' by [[Kazurou Inoue]]\n** ''[[Girls Saurus]]'' by [[Kei Kusunoki]] (moved to ''[[Monthly Sunday Gene-X]]'')\n** ''Shigeshida \u2606 Shokun!!'' by Moritaishi\n* 2002\n**''BREAKTHROUGH! ~Niji no Petal~'' by Y\u014dhei Suginobu\n* 2003\n**''Kowashiya Gamon'' by Shun Fujiki (moved to ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday]]'')\n** ''PEACE MAKER'' by Sh\u016bichir\u014d Sat\u014d\n* 2009\n**''Takkoku!!!'' by [[Tsubasa Fukuchi]]\n** ''Akira'' by Shir\u014d Otsuka\n** ''Mah\u014d Gy\u014dsh\u014dnin Roma'' by Toshihiko Kurazono\n** ''Mirai no Football'' by Eko Yamatoya\n** ''Ch\u014ddoky\u016b Sh\u014djo 4946'' by Takeshi Azuma\n** ''Ping Pong Rush'' by Aiko Koyama\n** ''Undead'' by Masashi Terajima\n** ''Samurai High School'' by Hiro Kashiwaba\n** ''Sh\u014dgaku ni Nyansei'' by Fujiminosuke Yorozuya\n** ''Mah\u014d no Iroha!'' by Inoue Kazurou\n** ''Super-Dreadnought Girl 4946'' by Azuma Takeshi\n* 2013\n**''[[Zettai Karen Children|The Unlimited: Hyobu Kyousuke]]'' by Rokurou Ogaki\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Shogakukan manga magazines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shonen Sunday Super}}\n[[Category:Japanese bi-monthly manga magazines]]\n[[Category:Japanese monthly manga magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Shogakukan magazines]]\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Sh\u014dnen manga magazines]]\n", "name_user": "2001:470:0:19c::2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sh%C5%8Dnen_Sunday_Super"}
{"title_page": "Isak Andic", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Andic|Ermay}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Isak Andic i Ermay.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| name         = Isak Andic Ermay\n| caption      = Isak Andic, Helena Rakosnik and Artur Mas (2010)\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth based on age as of date |62|2016|03|09|df=yes}}<ref name=Forbes />\n| birth_place  = [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  =\n| restingplace =\n| nationality  = Spanish\n| residence    = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| education    =\n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = Founder and largest shareholder, [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]]<ref name=Forbes/> \n| salary       =\n| networth     = [[United States dollar|$]]3.5 billion (March 2016)<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|title=Isak Andic|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/isak-andic/|website=Forbes|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n| spouse       = Neus Raig Tarrag\u00f3 (divorced)\n| parents      = \n| children     = Jonathan Andic<br> Judith Andic<br> Sarah Andic\n| relatives    = Nahman Andic (brother)\n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Isak Andic Ermay''' (born 1953) is a Spanish businessman, the founder and largest shareholder in the clothing retail chain [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn to a [[Sephardic]] [[Turkish Jews|Jewish]] family in [[Istanbul]],<ref name=MujerHoy>[http://www.mujerhoy.com/corazon/paparazzi/jonathan-andik-heredero-mango-708702012013.html MujerHoy: \"\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jonathan Andic, el heredero de Mango?\"] 08 January 2013</ref><ref name=BofFashion>[http://www.businessoffashion.com/isak-andic Business of Fashion: \"Isak Andic, Co-Founder, Mango - The entrepreneur co-founded the Spanish fast fashion chain by selling embroidered made-in-Turkey blouses in Barcelona\"] retrieved February 25, 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/The-worlds-50-Richest-Jews-31-40 Jerusalem Post: \"The world's 50 Richest Jews: 31-40\"] February 26, 2015</ref> Andic's family emigrated from Turkey to [[Barcelona, Spain]] in 1969<ref name=MujerHoy /> where he and his brother Nahman began selling hand-embroidered T-shirts<ref name=BofFashion /> and clogs.<ref name=MujerHoy /> They opened shops in Barcelona and Madrid, first selling their own brand (Isak jeans) and then stocking other brands.<ref name=BofFashion /> In 1984, he joined with fellow entrepreneur Enric Cus\u00ed and his brother and re-denominated all their stores under the name [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]].<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=BofFashion /> Andic chose the name \"Mango\" after tasting the fruit on a trip to the Philippines and for the fact that the word is pronounced the same in every language.<ref name=MujerHoy />\n\nIn 2006, Andic was appointed the director of [[Banco Sabadell]]<ref name=MujerHoy /> and in 2012, he became its single largest shareholder with a 7% ownership interest.<ref>[http://es.globedia.com/andic-compra-titulos-banco-sabadell-consolida-accionista Globedia: \"Andic compra un mill\u00f3n de t\u00edtulos del Banco Sabadell y se consolida como primer accionista\"] May 23, 2011</ref> According to [[Forbes]], Andic has a net worth of $4.8 billion, as of January 2015.<ref name=Forbes/> Mango has 2,400 stores in 107 countries.<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n== Membership ==\nIsak Andic is member of [[IESE Business School|IESE's]] International Advisory Board (IAB)<ref>[https://www.iese.edu/about/leadership/ ''Members of IESE's International Advisory Board''], iese.edu</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nAndic is divorced from Neus Raig Tarrag\u00f3 with whom he has three children:<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=ElConfidencial>[http://www.elconfidencial.com/economia/2012/10/20/andic-nombra-a-su-hijo-jonathan-como-sucesor-en-mango-107590 El Confidencial: \"Andic nombra a su hijo Jonathan como sucesor en Mango\" by Marcos Lamelas] October 20, 2012</ref> {{Interlanguage link multi|Jonathan Andic|es|3=Jonathan_Andic}} (born 1981) who was named his successor in 2012;<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=BofFashion /><ref name=ElConfidencial /> Judith Andic (born 1984), who also works for Mango; and Sarah Andic (born 1997).<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=ElConfidencial /> Andic lives in [[Barcelona]].<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andic, Isak}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish billionaires]]\n[[Category:Spanish Jews]]\n[[Category:Turkish Jews]]\n[[Category:Turkish expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:People from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n\n\n{{Spain-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image        = Isak Andic i Ermay.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| name         = Isak Andic\n| caption      = Isak Andic, Helena Rakosnik and Artur Mas (2010)\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth based on age as of date |62|2016|03|09|df=yes}}<ref name=Forbes />\n| birth_place  = [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  =\n| restingplace =\n| nationality  = Spanish\n| residence    = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| education    =\n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = Founder and largest shareholder, [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]]<ref name=Forbes/> \n| salary       =\n| networth     = [[United States dollar|$]]3.5 billion (March 2016)<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|title=Isak Andic|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/isak-andic/|website=Forbes|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n| spouse       = Neus Raig Tarrag\u00f3 (divorced)\n| parents      = \n| children     = Jonathan Andic<br> Judith Andic<br> Sarah Andic\n| relatives    = Nahman Andic (brother)\n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Isak Andic''' (born 1953) is a Spanish businessman, the founder and largest shareholder in the clothing retail chain [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn to a [[Sephardic]] [[Turkish Jews|Jewish]] family in [[Istanbul]],<ref name=MujerHoy>[http://www.mujerhoy.com/corazon/paparazzi/jonathan-andik-heredero-mango-708702012013.html MujerHoy: \"\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jonathan Andic, el heredero de Mango?\"] 08 January 2013</ref><ref name=BofFashion>[http://www.businessoffashion.com/isak-andic Business of Fashion: \"Isak Andic, Co-Founder, Mango - The entrepreneur co-founded the Spanish fast fashion chain by selling embroidered made-in-Turkey blouses in Barcelona\"] retrieved February 25, 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/The-worlds-50-Richest-Jews-31-40 Jerusalem Post: \"The world's 50 Richest Jews: 31-40\"] February 26, 2015</ref> Andic's family emigrated from Turkey to [[Barcelona, Spain]] in 1969<ref name=MujerHoy /> where he and his brother Nahman began selling hand-embroidered T-shirts<ref name=BofFashion /> and clogs.<ref name=MujerHoy /> They opened shops in Barcelona and Madrid, first selling their own brand (Isak jeans) and then stocking other brands.<ref name=BofFashion /> In 1984, he joined with fellow entrepreneur Enric Cus\u00ed and his brother and re-denominated all their stores under the name [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]].<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=BofFashion /> Andic chose the name \"Mango\" after tasting the fruit on a trip to the Philippines and for the fact that the word is pronounced the same in every language.<ref name=MujerHoy />\n\nIn 2006, Andic was appointed the director of [[Banco Sabadell]]<ref name=MujerHoy /> and in 2012, he became its single largest shareholder with a 7% ownership interest.<ref>[http://es.globedia.com/andic-compra-titulos-banco-sabadell-consolida-accionista Globedia: \"Andic compra un mill\u00f3n de t\u00edtulos del Banco Sabadell y se consolida como primer accionista\"] May 23, 2011</ref> According to [[Forbes]], Andic has a net worth of $4.8 billion, as of January 2015.<ref name=Forbes/> Mango has 2,400 stores in 107 countries.<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n== Membership ==\nIsak Andic is member of [[IESE Business School|IESE's]] International Advisory Board (IAB)<ref>[https://www.iese.edu/about/leadership/ ''Members of IESE's International Advisory Board''], iese.edu</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nAndic is divorced from Neus Raig Tarrag\u00f3 with whom he has three children:<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=ElConfidencial>[http://www.elconfidencial.com/economia/2012/10/20/andic-nombra-a-su-hijo-jonathan-como-sucesor-en-mango-107590 El Confidencial: \"Andic nombra a su hijo Jonathan como sucesor en Mango\" by Marcos Lamelas] October 20, 2012</ref> {{Interlanguage link multi|Jonathan Andic|es|3=Jonathan_Andic}} (born 1981) who was named his successor in 2012;<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=BofFashion /><ref name=ElConfidencial /> Judith Andic (born 1984), who also works for Mango; and Sarah Andic (born 1997).<ref name=MujerHoy /><ref name=ElConfidencial /> Andic lives in [[Barcelona]].<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andic, Isak}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish billionaires]]\n[[Category:Spanish Jews]]\n[[Category:Turkish Jews]]\n[[Category:Turkish expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:People from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish businesspeople]]\n\n\n{{Spain-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isak_Andic"}
{"title_page": "List of pornographic magazines", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2014}}\nThis is a '''list of pornographic magazines''' (or '''erotic magazine''', '''adult magazine''') \u2014 magazines that contain content of a sexual nature and are typically considered to be [[pornography]].\n\nFor inclusion in this list, [[pornographic magazines]] must be, or have been, widely available as a printed publication and contain hardcore or [[Softcore_pornography|softcore]] images.\n\n== Marketed to heterosexual men ==\nThese magazines may include female-male, female-female-male and/or female-female content.\n\n=== Americas ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n<big>'''Canada'''</big>\n* ''[[Summum (magazine)|Summum]]'' (2003\u2013present), Quebec\n<big>'''United States'''</big>\n* ''[[Adam Film World]]'' (1966\u20131998) and ''[[Adam Film World|Adam Film World Guide]]'' (1981-2008)\n* ''[[Asian Fever]]'' - LFP, {{ISSN|1521-6586}}, U.S., launch 1999\n* ''[[Barely Legal (magazine)|Barely Legal]]'' - ''[[Hustler]] Magazine'', {{ISSN|0149-4635}}, launch 1974\n* ''[[Beaver Hunt]]'', launch 1979\n* ''[[Celebrity Skin (magazine)|Celebrity Skin]]''\n* ''[[Chic (magazine)|Chic]]''\n* ''[[Club (magazine)|Club]]''\n* ''[[Gallery (magazine)|Gallery]]'' - Montcalm, launch 1972\n* ''[[Genesis (magazine)|Genesis]]'' - Magna, launch 1973\n* ''[[Gent (magazine)|Gent]]'' ([[Magna Publishing Group]])\n* ''[[High Society (magazine)|High Society]]'' - {{ISSN|1075-0800}}, oclc 18820931 (1976)\n* ''[[Hustler]]'' (1974\u2013present)\n* ''[[Juggs]]'', launch 1981\n* ''[[Leg Show]]''\n* ''[[Modern Man (magazine)|Modern Man]]'' (1952\u20131967)\n* ''[[Oui (magazine)|Oui]]'' (1972\u20132008)\n* ''[[Penthouse Forum]]''\n* ''[[Perfect 10]]''\n* ''[[Playboy]]'' (1953\u2013present)\n* ''[[Score (magazine)|Score]]'' (1992;  Miami, Florida, focuses on large-breasted women)\n* ''[[SCREW (magazine)|SCREW]]'' (Milky Way Productions, oclc 54031097 1968)\n* ''[[Swank (magazine)|Swank]]''\n}}\n\n=== Europe ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n<big>'''United Kingdom'''</big>\n* ''[[Asian Babes]]'' (Remnant Media, {{ISSN|1367-7284}}, UK, launch 1983)\n* ''[[Club International]]'' (1971; British sister of ''Club'')\n* ''[[Escort (magazine)|Escort]]'' (Paul Raymond Publications, UK, 1980\u2013present)\n* ''[[Fiesta (magazine)|Fiesta]] (Galaxy Publications, 1966)\n* ''[[Mayfair (magazine)|Mayfair]]'' (Paul Raymond Publications, UK)\n* ''[[Men Only]]'' (Paul Raymond Publications, UK)\n* ''[[Men's World]]'' (Paul Raymond Publications, UK)\n* ''[[Knave (magazine)|Knave]]'' (Galaxy Publications, oclc 76960716, 1959, UK)\n* ''[[Penthouse (magazine)|Penthouse]]'' (1965\u2013present) and ''[[Penthouse Variations]]''\n* ''[[Razzle (magazine)|Razzle]]'' (1983; British; focuses on amateur style pornography)\n<big>'''Netherlands'''</big>\n* ''[[Joop Wilhelmus#Chick|Chick]]'' (Netherlands, 1968\u20132008)\n* ''[[Joop Wilhelmus#Lolita|Lolita]]'' (Netherlands, 1970\u20131987)\n<big>'''Others'''</big>\n* ''[[Aktuell Rapport]]'' (Norwegian, 1976\u2013present), (Swedish, 1978\u2013present)\n* ''[[Cats (magazine)|Cats]]'' ([[Nordic Adult Entertainment]], 1982\u2013present) (Danish, Norwegian, Swedish)\n* ''[[Lui]]'' (1964-; French)\n* ''[[Color Climax]]'' (1966; Danish)\n* ''[[Private (magazine)|Private]]'' (1965\u2013present) (Swedish, Spanish)\n}}\n\n=== Asia ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n<big>'''Japan'''</big>\n* ''Beppin'' - 1984-94, thereafter ''[[Bejean]]'' 1994 - Eichi Shuppan, Japan, {{ISSN|0387-1460}}\n* ''[[Lemon People]]'' (Japan, 1981\u20131998)\n* ''[[Manga Burikko]]'' (Japan, 1983\u20131986)\n* ''[[Urecco]]'' - 1986, Million Shuppan, Japan\n* ''[[Video Boy]]'' - 1984, Eichi Shuppan, Japan\n* ''[[Weekly Shonen Sunday]]'' - 1959, [[Shogakukan]], Japan\n<big>'''India'''</big>\n* ''[[Debonair (magazine)|Debonair]]'' (India, 1973)\n}}\n\n== Lads' mags ==\n{{main|List of men's magazines#Lads' mags}}\n* ''[[Nuts (magazine)|Nuts]]''\n* ''[[Zoo Weekly]]'' - Emap East {{ISSN|1740-8512}} (UK, Australia, South Africa)\n\n== Marketed to gay and bisexual men ==\nGay pornographic magazines, sometimes known as adult magazines or gay sex magazines, contain content of a sexual nature, typically regarded as [[pornography]], that relates to men having sex with men.\n\nThese magazines are targeted to [[gay]] and [[bisexual]] men, although they may also have some female readers, and may include male-male and occasionally male-male-female content and/or male-female content. Such publications provide photographs or other illustrations of nudity and sexual activities, including [[oral sex]], [[anal sex]], and other various forms of such activities. These magazines primarily serve to stimulate sexual thoughts and emotions. Some magazines are very general in their variety of illustrations, while others may be more specific and focus on particular activities or fetishes.\n\nPrior to the 1970s, gay pornography was not widely distributed due to censorship laws. Non-pornographic \"[[beefcake magazines]]\" were widely available, and were generally purchased by gay men. From the late 1980s, a number of gay magazines and newspapers featured homoerotic nude or partially clothed male models but were not classified as pornography, for example ''[[Gay Times]]'' and ''[[QX Magazine]]''. These have not been included here. ''See [[List of LGBT periodicals]].''\n\nThe following is a list of gay pornographic magazines, with country of publication and approximate period of publication, where available:\n* ''[[Badi (magazine)|Badi]]'' (Japan, 1994)\n* ''[[Barazoku]]'' (Japan, 1971)\n* {{cite journal|title = [[Black Inches]]|publisher= Mavety Media Group|issn= 1084-2462}} (U.S., launch 1996-2009), focused on [[African-American]] men\n* {{cite journal|title = [[Blueboy (magazine)|Blueboy]]|publisher= Global Media Group|issn= 0279-3733}} (U.S., 1975 - 3 issues, bimonthly July/August 1975\u2013August/September 77, monthly November 1977 \u2013 2007)\n* ''[[Bound & Gagged (magazine)|Bound & Gagged]]'' (U.S., 1987 \u2013 2005)\n* ''[[Drum (American magazine)|Drum]]'' (U.S., 1964\u20131967), December 1965 issue was the first U.S. magazine to show male frontal nudity\n* ''[[Freshmen (magazine)|Freshmen]]'' (U.S., 1982-2009)\n* ''[[G Magazine#G Magazine, Brazil|G Magazine]]'' (Brazil, 1998\u20132014) ({{OCLC|45184945}})\n* ''Honcho'' (United States, April 1978 to November 2009)<ref>[http://www.gayeroticarchives.com/22_listings/Monthlies/Honcho.html ''Honcho'' at Gay Erotic Archives]</ref>\n* ''[[Mandate (magazine)|Mandate]]'' (U.S., monthly April 1975\u2013October 2009), published by Mavety Media Group, Inc. ({{ISSN|0360-1005}})\n* ''[[M\u00e4nner (magazine)|M\u00e4nner Aktuell]]'' (Germany, 1987 - 2017)\n* {{cite journal|title = [[Men (magazine)|Men]]|publisher= Specialty Media|issn= 1097-3370}}, U.S., monthly, October 1997 - November 2009, began as ''Advocate Men'' in June 1984\n* ''Mister'' (out of print)\n* ''[[Pinups Magazine]]''\n* ''[[Playguy]]'' (U.S., October 1976 \u2013 October 2009)\n* ''[[Samson (magazine)|Samson]]'' (Japan, 1982)\n* ''Vulcan'' (UK), made famous in a High Court test case by serial killer [[Dennis Nilsen]]<ref name=loneve>{{cite news|last1=Cheston|first1=Paul|title=Mass killer fights for porn in jail|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mass-killer-fights-for-porn-in-jail-6312916.html|accessdate=20 October 2014|agency=Evening Standard Ltd|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=25 October 2001|ref=loneve}}</ref> (out of print)\n\n== Marketed to heterosexual women ==\n* ''[[Filament (magazine)|Filament]]'', U.K., 2009\u20132011\n* ''[[Playgirl]]'', {{ISSN|0273-6918}}, U.S., quarterly 1973\u2013present<ref>{{cite magazine|title=A 'Playgirl' for Adult TV|author=R. Thomas Umstead|magazine=Multichannel News|date=2003-11-17|accessdate=2009-02-08|quote=The new venture, Trans Digital Media LLC, will convert Blue Horizon's popular Playgirl magazine brand into Playgirl TV... Along with females, Graff also said the network will all tap an under served audience of homosexual men. 'Fifty percent of Playgirl's readership is male, so it's an interesting way of tapping into the gay market without having to scream, \"We have a gay channel.\"'|url=http://www.multichannel.com/article/79434-A_Playgirl_for_Adult_TV.php}}</ref>\n* ''[[Viva (magazine)|Viva]]'', US, 1973\u20131980\n\n== Marketed to lesbian women ==\n* ''[[On Our Backs]]''\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Fetish magazine]]\n* [[Gay pornography]]\n* [[List of performers in gay porn films]]\n* [[List of pornographic movie studios]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Refend}}\n{{Pornography}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of magazines|Pornographic]]\n[[Category:Pornographic magazines|*]]\n[[Category:Pornography-related lists|Magazines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2014}}\nThis is a '''list of pornographic magazines''' (or '''erotic magazine''', '''adult magazine''') \u2014 magazines that contain content of a sexual nature and are typically considered to be [[pornography]].\n\nFor inclusion in this list, [[pornographic magazines]] must be, or have been, widely available as a printed publication and contain hardcore or [[Softcore_pornography|softcore]] images.\n\n== Marketed to heterosexual men ==\nThese magazines may include female-male, female-female-male and/or female-female content.\n\n=== Americas ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n<big>'''Canada'''</big>\n* ''[[Summum (magazine)|Summum]]'' (2003\u2013present), Quebec\n<big>'''United States'''</big>\n* ''[[Adam Film World]]'' (1966\u20131998) and ''[[Adam Film World|Adam Film World Guide]]'' (1981-2008)\n* ''[[Asian Fever]]'' - LFP, {{ISSN|1521-6586}}, U.S., launch 1999\n* ''[[Barely Legal (magazine)|Barely Legal]]'' - ''[[Hustler]] Magazine'', {{ISSN|0149-4635}}, launch 1974\n* ''[[Beaver Hunt]]'', launch 1979\n* ''[[Celebrity Skin (magazine)|Celebrity Skin]]''\n