on= Pittsburgh, PA  |page= 261 |year= 2004 |isbn= 0-9752627-5-0}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last= Kurland |editor1-first= Philip B. |editor2-last= Lerner |editor2-first= Ralph |lastauthoramp= yes |title= The Founders' Constitution |publisher= University of Chicago Press and the Liberty Fund |isbn= 0-86597-279-6 |postscript= ; |year= 1987 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/foundersconstitu0003unse }} The work consists of \"extracts from the leading works of political theory, history, law, and constitutional argument on which the Framers and their contemporaries drew and which they themselves produced\".\n* {{cite book |editorlink1= Leonard Levy |editor1-last=Levy |editor1-first= Leonard W. |editor2-first= Kenneth L.  |editor2-last= Karst |editor3-first= John G. |editor3-last= West |lastauthoramp= yes |title= Encyclopedia of the American Constitution |location= New York |publisher= Macmillan |year= 1992}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last= Mason |editor1-first= Alpheus Thomas |editor2-first= Donald Grier |editor2-last= Stephenson |lastauthoramp= yes |title= American Constitutional Law: Introductory Essays and Selected Cases |edition= 14th |year= 2004}}{{Full citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n* {{cite book |ref= harv |last= McDonald |first= Forrest |authorlink= Forrest McDonald |title= Novus Ordo Seclorum: The Intellectual Origins of the Constitution |url= https://archive.org/details/novusordosecloru0000mcdo |url-access= registration |publisher= University Press of Kansas |location= Lawrence |year= 1985 |isbn= 978-0-7006-0311-4 }}\n* [[Jed S. Rakoff|Rakoff, Jed S.]], \"The Last of His Kind\" (review of John Paul Stevens, ''The Making of a Justice: Reflections on My First 94 Years'', Little, Brown, 549 pp.), ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', vol. LXVI, no. 14 (26 September 2019), pp. 20, 22, 24. [[John Paul Stevens]], \"a throwback to the postwar liberal Republican [U.S. Supreme Court] appointees\", questioned the validity of \"the doctrine of [[sovereign immunity]], which holds that you cannot sue any state or federal government agency, or any of its officers or employees, for any wrong they may have committed against you, unless the state or federal government consents to being sued\" (p. 20); the propriety of \"the increasing resistance of the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] to most meaningful forms of [[gun control]]\" (p. 22); and \"the constitutionality of the [[death penalty]]... because of incontrovertible evidence that innocent people have been sentenced to death.\" (pp. 22, 24.)  \n* {{cite book |last= Robertson |first= David Brian |title= The Original Compromise: What the Constitutional Framers Were Really Thinking |location= New York |publisher= Oxford University Press |year= 2013}}\n* {{cite book |authorlink= Laurence Tribe |last= Tribe |first= Laurence H. |title= American Constitutional Law |year= 1999}}{{Full citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n* {{cite web |author= Yale Law School |url= http://avalon.law.yale.edu/subject_menus/debcont.asp |title= The Avalon Project: Notes on the Debates in the Federal Convention |work= The Avalon Project |publisher= Yale Law School |accessdate= May 8, 2011}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |commons=United States Constitution |b=United States Government/The Constitution and Amendments |n=no |q=United States Constitution |s=Constitution of the United States of America |v=no |species=no }}\n\n===U.S. government sources===\n* [https://www.congress.gov/constitution-annotated/ Analysis and Interpretation of the Constitution of the United States]: legal analysis and interpretation of the Constitution, based primarily on Supreme Court case law\n* [https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/ourdocs/Constitution.html United States Constitution]: Library of Congress web guide to Constitution related primary documents and resources\n* [https://www.archives.gov/exhibits/charters/charters.html America's Founding Documents]: original text and articles exploring the Declaration of Independence, Constitution, and Bill of Rights\n* [https://www.senate.gov/civics/constitution_item/constitution.htm Constitution of the United States]: original text of each clause in the Constitution with an accompanying explanation of its meaning and how that meaning has changed over time\n\n===Non-governmental sources===\n* {{Britannica|134197|Constitution of the United States of America}}\n* [https://constitutionus.com Constitution:  accessible text with index, web images of originals, and explanations of spelling and vocabulary]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080531072633/http://www.law.uchicago.edu/constitution Audio reading] of the Constitution in [[MP3]] format provided by the [[University of Chicago Law School]]\n* [//uscon.mobi/ Mobile friendly] version of the Constitution\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080118090302/http://www.constitutioncenter.org/ National Constitution Center]\n\n{{US Constitution|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Historical American Documents}}\n{{United States topics}}\n{{James Madison}}\n{{Gouverneur Morris}}\n{{Americas topic|Constitution of|title=Constitutions of states and dependencies in the Americas}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constitution, United States}}\n[[Category:1787 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1789 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1789 in American law]]\n[[Category:1789 in American politics]]\n[[Category:1789 in the United States]]\n[[Category:American political philosophy literature]]\n[[Category:Constitutions by country|United States]]\n[[Category:James Madison]]\n[[Category:Government documents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Political charters|United States Constitution]]\n[[Category:United States Constitution| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: case by case \u2192 case-by-case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitution_of_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics", "text_new": "{{short description|Scientific and professional organization}}\n{{Redirect|ASHI}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics\n| image = American_Society_for_Histocompatibility_and_Immunogenetics.png\n| headquarters = 1120 Route 73, Suite 200 Mt. Laurel, NJ 08054\n| coords = \n| membership = Over 1,000\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = Medhat Askar\n| leader_title2 = Executive Director\n| leader_name2 = Katherine Giovetsis\n| formation = {{start date and age|1972}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.ashi-hla.org}}\n}}\nThe '''American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics''' ('''ASHI''') is a not-for-profit association of clinical and research professionals involved in the science, education and application of histocompatibility, immunogenetics and transplantation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/about_ashi|title=About ASHI - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Profile ==\n\n=== Governance ===\nASHI is a non-profit corporation incorporated in the State of Missouri. ASHI's bylaws describe rules to ensure democratic process. The organizational entities include:\n\n* ASHI President. The ASHI's president is elected by members. The president chairs the Board of Directors and the Executive Committee of the Board of Directors. During his or her term of office, the president performs duties as prescribed by the bylaws.\n* Board of Directors. The board is composed of six executive officers, the President, Vice-President of Operations, President-Elect, Secretary, Treasurer and Immediate Past-President, and nine At-Large Directors. The Board is the active governing body of the Society responsible for the Society's administrative affairs and manages the assets of the Society.\n* Executive Committee of the Board of Directors. The Committee acts for the Board of Directors in any urgent matters. It is composed of the six executive officers of the Board of Directors.\n* ASHI Committee Structure: Boards and Committees. Members of boards and committees conduct much of ASHI's work voluntarily. They carry out a wide variety of tasks. Some have responsibility for monitoring major programs, such as the accreditation process, the publications and international affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cdn.ymaws.com/www.ashi-hla.org/resource/resmgr/docs/ashi_bylaws/2018_ashi_bylaws_-_approved.pdf|title=ASHI bylaws|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Organizational Structure ===\nASHI comprises an executive office, a publishing operation, business, information technology, and operational needs, and five divisions:\n\n* the Science & Education Division plans the annual meeting program, provides accreditation programmes and certificates and promotes continuing education for histocompatibility and immunogenetics professionals;\n* the Professional Standards Division reviews accreditation, controls quality of laboratory members, and tests proficiency in immunogenetics;\n* the Communications Division manages external and national clinical affairs, and publications;\n* the Membership Division is responsible for outreach to its members;\n* the Operations Division provides support for its members in the form of awards, information technology and leadership development, and also performs audits, manages bylaws and finances.\n\n=== Membership ===\nMembership with the ASHI requires active engagement in the field of histocompatibility and/or immunogenetics testing.\n\n=== Awards ===\nASHI sponsors several awards to recognize scientific accomplishments and contributions to the field of histocompatibility and immunogenetics and service to the society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/awards|title=Awards - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* Rose Payne Award\n* Bernard Amos Distinguished Scientist Award\n* Paul I. Terasaki Clinical Science Award\n* Distinguished Service Award\n* Outstanding Technologist Award\n* J Marilyn MacQueen Rising Star Award (formerly ASHI/SEOPF J. Marilyn MacQueen Award)\n* Scholar Awards & International Scholar Award\n* Travel Fund Award\n* Young Investigator Awards\n\n=== Publications ===\nASHI sponsors the following publications:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/Publications|title=Publications - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Human Immunology'''\n\n[[Human Immunology]] accepts contributions of original work in the field of [[immunogenetics]]. The journal is published 12 times a year by [[Elsevier Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/human-immunology|title=Human Immunology {{!}} Journal {{!}} ScienceDirect.com|website=www.sciencedirect.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Full text articles are available online for members. Abstracts from Annual Meetings may also be found in ''Human Immunology''.\n\n'''ASHI Quarterly'''\n\n''ASHI Quarterly'' contains news, scientific articles and information of interest to the membership.\n\n'''ASHI Insights'''\n\nASHI Insights is an e-newsletter containing societal related news and links to scientific articles. It is distributed to members every other week.\n\n=== Accreditation Program ===\nThe Accreditation Program was created to promote quality laboratory [[Human leukocyte antigen|HLA typing]] practice in histocompatibility and immunogenetics by evaluating laboratory personnel, procedures and facilities to determine if they are in compliance with those published standards of ASHI and with those standards of organizations by which ASHI is deemed and which apply to the activities of that laboratory\n\n=== Proficiency Testing Program ===\nThe program utilizes clinically-based samples to assess a laboratory's ability to accurately perform its analyses. All surveys are graded using established criteria with oversight by ASHl's Proficiency Testing Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/PT|title=Proficiency Testing Program - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[European Federation for Immunogenetics]]\n* [[Human Immunology]]\n* [[Histocompatibility]]\n* [[Immunogenetics]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Immunology organizations]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in the United States\u200e]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scientific and professional organization}}\n{{Redirect|ASHI}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics\n| image = American_Society_for_Histocompatibility_and_Immunogenetics.png\n| headquarters = 1120 Route 73, Suite 200 Mt. Laurel, NJ 08054\n| coords = \n| membership = Over 1,000\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = Medhat Askar\n| leader_title2 = Executive Director\n| leader_name2 = Katherine Giovetsis\n| formation = {{start date and age|1972}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.ashi-hla.org}}\n}}\nThe '''American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics''' ('''ASHI''') is a not-for-profit association of clinical and research professionals involved in the science, education and application of histocompatibility, immunogenetics and transplantation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/about_ashi|title=About ASHI - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Profile ==\n\n=== Governance ===\nASHI is a non-profit corporation incorporated in the State of Missouri. ASHI's bylaws describe rules to ensure democratic process. The organizational entities include:\n\n* ASHI President. The ASHI's president is elected by members. The president chairs the Board of Directors and the Executive Committee of the Board of Directors. During his or her term of office, the president performs duties as prescribed by the bylaws.\n* Board of Directors. The board is composed of six executive officers, the President, Vice-President of Operations, President-Elect, Secretary, Treasurer and Immediate Past-President, and nine At-Large Directors. The Board is the active governing body of the Society responsible for the Society's administrative affairs and manages the assets of the Society.\n* Executive Committee of the Board of Directors. The Committee acts for the Board of Directors in any urgent matters. It is composed of the six executive officers of the Board of Directors.\n* ASHI Committee Structure: Boards and Committees. Members of boards and committees conduct much of ASHI's work voluntarily. They carry out a wide variety of tasks. Some have responsibility for monitoring major programs, such as the accreditation process, the publications and international affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cdn.ymaws.com/www.ashi-hla.org/resource/resmgr/docs/ashi_bylaws/2018_ashi_bylaws_-_approved.pdf|title=ASHI bylaws|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Organizational Structure ===\nASHI comprises an executive office, a publishing operation, business, information technology, and operational needs, and five divisions:\n\n* the Science & Education Division plans the annual meeting program, provides accreditation programmes and certificates and promotes continuing education for histocompatibility and immunogenetics professionals;\n* the Professional Standards Division reviews accreditation, controls quality of laboratory members, and tests proficiency in immunogenetics;\n* the Communications Division manages external and national clinical affairs, and publications;\n* the Membership Division is responsible for outreach to its members;\n* the Operations Division provides support for its members in the form of awards, information technology and leadership development, and also performs audits, manages bylaws and finances.\n\n=== Membership ===\nMembership with the ASHI requires active engagement in the field of histocompatibility and/or immunogenetics testing.\n\n=== Awards ===\nASHI sponsors several awards to recognize scientific accomplishments and contributions to the field of histocompatibility and immunogenetics and service to the society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/awards|title=Awards - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* Rose Payne Award\n* Bernard Amos Distinguished Scientist Award\n* Paul I. Terasaki Clinical Science Award\n* Distinguished Service Award\n* Outstanding Technologist Award\n* J Marilyn MacQueen Rising Star Award (formerly ASHI/SEOPF J. Marilyn MacQueen Award)\n* Scholar Awards & International Scholar Award\n* Travel Fund Award\n* Young Investigator Awards\n\n=== Publications ===\nASHI sponsors the following publications:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/Publications|title=Publications - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Human Immunology'''\n\n[[Human Immunology]] accepts contributions of original work in the field of [[immunogenetics]]. The journal is published 12 times a year by [[Elsevier Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/human-immunology|title=Human Immunology {{!}} Journal {{!}} ScienceDirect.com|website=www.sciencedirect.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Full text articles are available online for members. Abstracts from Annual Meetings may also be found in ''Human Immunology''.\n\n'''ASHI Quarterly'''\n\n''ASHI Quarterly'' contains news, scientific articles and information of interest to the membership.\n\n'''ASHI Insights'''\n\nASHI Insights is an e-newsletter containing societal related news and links to scientific articles. It is distributed to members every other week.\n\n=== Accreditation Program ===\nThe Accreditation Program was created to promote quality laboratory HLA typing practice in histocompatibility and immunogenetics by evaluating laboratory personnel, procedures and facilities to determine if they are in compliance with those published standards of ASHI and with those standards of organizations by which ASHI is deemed and which apply to the activities of that laboratory\n\n=== Proficiency Testing Program ===\nThe program utilizes clinically-based samples to assess a laboratory's ability to accurately perform its analyses. All surveys are graded using established criteria with oversight by ASHl's Proficiency Testing Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/PT|title=Proficiency Testing Program - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[European Federation for Immunogenetics]]\n* [[Human Immunology]]\n* [[Histocompatibility]]\n* [[Immunogenetics]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Immunology organizations]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in the United States\u200e]]\n", "name_user": "SaladH", "label": "safe", "comment": "link to HLA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Society_for_Histocompatibility_and_Immunogenetics"}
{"title_page": "2016 Ole Miss Rebels football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=2016\n  |team=Ole Miss Rebels\n  |sport=football\n  |image = Ole Miss Rebels logo.svg\n  |image_size = 200\n  |conference=Southeastern Conference\n  |short_conf=SEC\n  |division=Western Division\n  |CoachRank= \n  |APRank= \n  |CFPRank=\n  |record= 0\u20137\n  |conf_record= 0\u20136\n  |wins_vacated=5\n  |conf_wins_vacated=2\n  |head_coach=[[Hugh Freeze]]\n  |hc_year=5th\n  |cooff_coach1=[[Matt Luke (football coach)|Matt Luke]]\n  |cooc1_year=5th\n  |cooff_coach2=Dan Werner\n  |cooc2_year=5th\n  |codef_coach1=[[Dave Wommack]]\n  |codc1_year=5th\n  |codef_coach2=Jason Jones\n  |codc2_year=4th\n  |off_scheme= Tempo\n  |def_scheme=Multiple\n  |stadium=[[Vaught\u2013Hemingway Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 64,038)\n  |bowl=\n  |bowl_result=\n  |champion=\n}}\n{{2016 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2016 Ole Miss Rebels football team''' represented the [[University of Mississippi]] in the [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Rebels played their home games at the newly renovated [[Vaught\u2013Hemingway Stadium]] in [[Oxford, Mississippi]] and competed in the Western Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). They were led by fifth-year head coach [[Hugh Freeze]] in what would turn out to be his final season with the Rebels.<ref>https://www.si.com/college-football/2017/07/20/hugh-freeze-ole-miss-resigns-matt-luke-interim-head-coach</ref> They finished the season 0\u20137, 0\u20136 in SEC play to finish in last place in the Western Division. \n\nOn February 11, 2019, Ole Miss announced the vacation of all wins in the years 2010, 2011, 2012, and 2016. In 2013, all wins except the Music City Bowl were vacated. In 2014, all wins except the Presbyterian game were vacated.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://olemiss.rivals.com/news/ole-miss-vacates-more-than-30-wins-over-a-span-of-six-seasons | work=Rivals |title=Ole Miss vacates more than 30 wins over a span of six seasons  | first=Chase| last=Parham| date=February 11, 2019 | accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Previous season and offseason==\n\n===2015 season===\n{{Main|2015 Ole Miss Rebels football team}}\nOle Miss's 2015 season began with easy victories over [[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] foe UT-Martin and the [[Mountain West Conference|Mountain West]]'s [[Fresno State Bulldogs football|Fresno State]], and continued their momentum by defeating then-no.2 [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] on the road, which would become the signature victory of the Rebels' 2015 campaign. Ole Miss then rose to no.3 in the AP Poll, and although they were heavy favorites in their next matchup against [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]], they struggled mightily, but ultimately emerged victorious. They Rebels maintained their no.3 ranking before getting blown out by [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] on the road and fell to no.14 before bouncing back against [[New Mexico State Aggies football|New Mexico State]]. The Rebels entered their next game with a #13 ranking against rival [[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]], in what was one of the most anticipated in the history of Memphis football. Ole Miss, despite being double digit favorites, lost by 13 points, causing them to fall 11 spots in the rankings to no.24. The Rebels followed with two wins against SEC West opponents [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] and [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] and climbed to no.18 in the rankings and controlled their own destiny the SEC West, but a heartbreaking loss to [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] the following week caused them to fall to second place in the SEC West and to fall out of the rankings for the first time since the [[2013 Ole Miss Rebels football team|2013 season]]. However, Ole Miss finished the regular season with double digit wins over ranked SEC Rivals [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] and [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] and rose to no.12 in the [[College Football Playoff]] poll, which earned them a [[2016 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] berth for the first time since 1970, where they defeated no.16 [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]] and ultimately finished ranked no.10 in the AP Poll, their first top-ten finish since 1969.\n\n===NCAA investigation===\nThe offseason was a controversial one for the Rebels, where an ongoing NCAA investigation dominated college football headlines. The investigation began prior to the start of the 2015 season, where Ole Miss star offensive tackle [[Laremy Tunsil]] was arrested on charges of [[domestic violence]] after allegedly assaulting his stepfather, Lindsey Miller. Ole Miss coach [[Hugh Freeze]] announced that Tunsil was defending his mother, Desiree Tunsil. A police report that was released days after the incident stated that Miller claimed Tunsil was \"riding around with football agents\" and that when a deputy arrived at the scene of the incident, \"Tunsil and the agents\" left in a yellow convertible. Days later, NCAA officials interviewed Miller about allegations of multiple violations of rules by the Ole Miss football program; Hugh Freeze later dismissed the possibility of a violation of rules, saying he's confident his program \"always does the right thing\". In August 2015, Tunsil and Miller agreed to drop charges against each other and sign dismissal forms. However, Tunsil was suspended from the first seven games of the 2015 season, making his debut against Texas A&M. In October 2015, Ole Miss announced that Tunsil used three loaner vehicles over a six-month period without payment, among other impermissible benefits.\n\nOnly a few days later, an NCAA investigation of Louisiana Lafayette revealed that former Ole Miss coach David Saunders may have potentially committed violations while at Ole Miss. Saunders allegedly helped five recruits receive fraudulent ACT scores at Wayne County High School, lied to the NCAA about his involvement and failed to cooperate with the subsequent investigation. He also allegedly gave a total of $6,500 to a player over the course of two semesters while at Louisiana Lafayette.\n\nIn January 2016, after the Rebels' Sugar Bowl victory over Oklahoma State, Ole Miss received a notice of allegations from the NCAA. However, Ole Miss athletic director [[Ross Bjork]] stated that the majority of the violations occurred before his arrival at Ole Miss and before the hiring of Hugh Freeze. In February, Bjork said that the NCAA has completed its investigation of Ole Miss's football program, and also stated that he did not expect a \"second letter\" from the NCAA concerning additional violations and that Freeze was not named by the NCAA in any wrongdoing.\n\nAt this point, the investigation was seemingly coming to an end, but on the night of the [[NFL Draft]], Laremy Tunsil's [[Instagram]] account was hacked, and a video of him smoking a bong fashioned out of a gas mask is posted, as well as photos of text messages where Tunsil asks for money from an Ole Miss administrator. When asked if he ever received money while at Ole Miss, Tunsil admitted that he did, in fact, receive money.\n\nAs a result of the investigation, Ole Miss self-imposed an 11-scholarship reduction over the course of four seasons. Along with the reduction of scholarships, the school has also suspended two unnamed assistants from recruiting, fined itself $159,352 and required current staff to go through additional training on NCAA rules and policy. In August 2016, it was announced that NCAA investigators have interviewed players at rival SEC schools about their recruitment by Ole Miss. NCAA Enforcement representatives have visited Auburn and Mississippi State, along with perhaps one other unnamed SEC West school during the summer of 2016. The players were granted immunity from possible NCAA sanctions in exchange for truthful accounts of their recruitment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/amp/s/www.yahoo.com/amphtml/sports/news/sources-ncaas-ole-miss-investigation-expands-beyond-laremy-tunsil-124229650.html?client=safari|title=Sources: NCAA's Ole Miss Investigation expands beyone Laremy Tunsil|last=Forde|first=Pat|work=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|date=August 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/story/sports/college/ole-miss/2016/05/27/timeline-ncaa-and-ole-miss/85030046/|title=Timeline: NCAA and Ole Miss|last=Klement|first=Kim|work=[[The Clarion Ledger]]|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016 recruiting class===\nThe 2016 National Signing Day was Wednesday, February 3, 2016. The Rebels signed a total of 24 prospects to a letter of intent, headlined by 5-star quarterback [[Shea Patterson]] and 5-star offensive tackle Gregory Little and 5 star defensive tackle Benito Jones. According to [[247Sports.com]]. The Rebels' 2016 recruiting class is considered to be the best in school history, surpassing the 2013 class.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ole Miss lands top quarterback, offensive lineman |agency=Associated Press |date=February 3, 2016 |url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/good-day-ole-miss-lands-top-quarterback-offensive-lineman }}</ref>\n\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|40=yes|collapse=yes|year=2016}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = Gregory Little\n| position   = OT\n| hometown   = [[Allen, Texas]]\n| highschool = [[Allen High School (Texas)|Allen High School]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 5.5\n| weight = 305\n| 40     = \u2013\n| commitdate   = 12/16/2015\n| scout stars  = 5\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 5\n| espn stars   = 5\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = Shea Patterson\n| position   = QB\n| hometown   = [[Bradenton, Florida]]\n| highschool = [[IMG Academy]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 1.5\n| weight = 192\n| 40     = \u2013\n| commitdate   = 2/17/2015\n| scout stars  = 5\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 5\n| espn stars   = 4\n}