{"title_page": "Jacinda", "text_new": "Jacinda means beautiful a person with great leadership an inspirational leader. \nPeople with this name have authority or power to lead they can also be defined as a light source they are usually emotional\n", "text_old": "'''Jacinda''' is a given name. Notable people with the name include:\n\n* [[Jacinda Ardern]] (born 1980), Prime Minister of New Zealand \n* [[Jacinda Barclay]] (born 1991), Australian football and baseball player\n* [[Jacinda Barrett]] (born 1972), Australian-American actress and model\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jacinta]]\n\n{{given name}}\n", "name_user": "41.215.173.87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacinda"}
{"title_page": "Gunung Gangsir", "text_new": "{{Infobox Historic building\n|image=035 Main Entrance, Gunung Gangsir (39519459575).jpg\n|caption=Gunung Gangsir temple from front\n|name=Candi Gunung Gangsir\n|map_type=\n|map_size=\n|latitude=\n|longitude=\n|location_town=[[Pasuruan Regency|Pasuruan]], [[East Java]]. \n|location_country=[[Indonesia]]\n|architect=\n|client=\n|engineer=\n|construction_start_date=  \n|completion_date=  \n|date_demolished=\n|cost=\n|structural_system= \n|style=[[Candi of Indonesia|Candi]]\n|size=15 x 15 x 15 m\n| coordinates = {{coord|7|35|12|S|112|44|0|E|source:frwiki_region:ID|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Gunung Gangsir''' ({{lang-id|Candi Gunung Gangsir}}) is an 11th-century [[Hinduism|Hindu]] [[Candi of Indonesia|candi]] (temple) located approximately 5 kilometers west from the town of [[Bangil]]. This red brick structure is located in Gunung Gangsir village, Beji subdistrict,  [[Pasuruan Regency]], [[East Java]] [[Indonesia]].<ref name=\"Perpusnas-Gangsir\">{{Cite web|url=https://candi.perpusnas.go.id/temples_en/deskripsi-east_java-gununggangsir_temple_15|title=Gununggangsir Temple|date=2014|website=[[National Library of Indonesia]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Formerly, this temple was known as '''Keboncandi''' temple.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eastjava.com/tourism/pasuruan/gangsir-temple.html |title=Gunung Gangsir Temple |website=www.eastjava.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nGunung Gangsir is quite unique among East Javanese temples, because it was the only temple that combines East Javanese and Central Javanese [[Candi of Indonesia|candi]] styles. It is also the only known temple in East Java that uses clay casting techniques to display a variety of decorations.\n\nThis unique distinctions has led for the experts to suggests that the temple is actually far older than the nearby [[Pari Temple|Pari]] and [[Jabung]] temples of Majapahit period, thus dated the temple circa 11th century CE, approximately during the reign of King [[Airlangga]] of [[Kahuripan]] Kingdom.<ref name=\"Perpusnas-Gangsir\"/> Regarding the structure of this temple,  Marijke J. Klokke, a Dutch archaeologist, suggests that Gunung Gangsir Temple possibly had been restored during the end of East Javanese kingdom period by using material from an older temple.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rujivacharakul|first=Vimalin|url=https://books.google.co.id/books?id=FCoWAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA257&lpg=PA257&dq=Marijke+J.+Klokke+Gunung+Gangsir&source=bl&ots=dMqrQjddpr&sig=ACfU3U0mNre-edzLKvPwfi8iIsphm2NEMQ&hl=id&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwinmuCI5tXoAhWAIbcAHeOmDckQ6AEwAXoECAsQMw#v=onepage&q=Marijke%20J.%20Klokke%20Gunung%20Gangsir&f=false|title=Architecturalized Asia: Mapping a Continent through History|last2=Hahn|first2=H. Hazel|last3=Oshima|first3=Ken Tadashi|last4=Christensen|first4=Peter|date=2013-11-01|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-988-8208-05-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and design==\n[[File:036 View from South, Gunung Gangsir (39519447915).jpg|thumb|left|Gunung Gangsir temple viewed from the south.]]\nThe temple structure was made from red [[brick]]s, which is a common temple building materials in the region during [[Majapahit]] period (c. 14th  to 15th century), as demontrated by [[Pari Temple|Pari]] and [[Jabung]] temple nearby. However, the design, shape and proportion, also the decorations is more similar to Central Javanese temples from earlier period. The proportion for example, is quite similar to the 8th century [[Mendut]] temple near Borobudur.\n\nThe temple is facing East-Southeast direction, with a flight of stairs and portal facing that direction protruding on the east side of temple structure. The temple base is rectangular in shape with dimension of 15 metres x 15 metres. The temple is 15 metres in height, with visible distinction between foot (base) part, body, and roof. The elevated terrace and the room is about 5 metres in high from the ground, accessible through the stairs. Inside the temple, there is a spacious temple cella served as ''garbagriha'' or inner sanctum.<ref name=\"Perpusnas-Gangsir\"/> The roof is arranged in stepped pyramid arranged in three stages, the top stage and its pinnacle however is now missing.\n[[File:Candi Gunung Gangsir D.JPG|thumb|upright|Temple decorations of vessels with floral motif, made by clay mold casting technique.]]\nThe temple is quite richly decorated with niches, seams and decorated antifixes. Intricate panels, featuring ornaments in the form of bas-reliefs, vessels with floral motifs, pilasters, images of trees and animals, which are made with clay molding techniques. There are traces of plasters know as ''vajralepa'', which suggest originally the entire surface of the temple was covered with plaster, which is similar to the [[Kalasan]] and [[Sari temple]] near Prambanan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/886882212|title=Candi Indonesia|last=Sedyawati, Edi, 1938-|others=Latief, Feri, Indonesia. Direktorat Pelestarian Cagar Budaya dan Permuseuman,|isbn=9786021766934|edition=Cetakan pertama|lang=id|location=Jakarta|oclc=886882212}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pari Temple]]\n* [[Jawi Temple]]\n* [[Jabung]]\n* [[Trowulan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Candi Gunung Gangsir}}\n\n{{Hindu temples in Indonesia}}\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Indonesia|Gunung Gangsir]]\n[[Category:Kahuripan]]\n[[Category:Cultural Properties of Indonesia in East Java]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Historic building\n|image=035 Main Entrance, Gunung Gangsir (39519459575).jpg\n|caption=Gunung Gangsir temple from front\n|name=Candi Gunung Gangsir\n|map_type=\n|map_size=\n|latitude=\n|longitude=\n|location_town=[[Pasuruan Regency|Pasuruan]], [[East Java]]. \n|location_country=[[Indonesia]]\n|architect=\n|client=\n|engineer=\n|construction_start_date=  \n|completion_date=  \n|date_demolished=\n|cost=\n|structural_system= \n|style=[[Candi of Indonesia|Candi]]\n|size=15 x 15 x 15 m\n| coordinates = {{coord|7|35|12|S|112|44|0|E|source:frwiki_region:ID|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Gunung Gangsir''' ({{lang-id|Candi Gunung Gangsir}}) is an 11th-century [[Hinduism|Hindu]] [[Candi of Indonesia|candi]] (temple) located approximately 5 kilometers west from the town of [[Bangil]]. This red brick structure is located in Gunung Gangsir village, Beji subdistrict,  [[Pasuruan Regency]], [[East Java]] [[Indonesia]].<ref name=\"Perpusnas-Gangsir\">{{Cite web|url=https://candi.perpusnas.go.id/temples_en/deskripsi-east_java-gununggangsir_temple_15|title=Gununggangsir Temple|date=2014|website=[[National Library of Indonesia]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Formerly, this temple was known as '''Keboncandi''' temple.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eastjava.com/tourism/pasuruan/gangsir-temple.html |title=Gunung Gangsir Temple |website=www.eastjava.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nGunung Gangsir is quite unique among East Javanese temples, because it was the only temple that combines East Javanese and Central Javanese [[Candi of Indonesia|candi]] styles. It is also the only known temple in East Java that uses clay casting techniques to display a variety of decorations.\n\nThis unique distinctions has led for the experts to suggests that the temple is actually far older than the nearby [[Pari Temple|Pari]] and [[Jabung]] temples of Majapahit period, thus place the temples around 11th century CE, approximately during the reign of King [[Airlangga]] of [[Kahuripan]] Kingdom.<ref name=\"Perpusnas-Gangsir\"/> Regarding the structure of this temple,  Marijke J. Klokke, a Dutch archaeologist, suggests that Gunung Gangsir Temple possibly had been restored during the end of East Javanese kingdom period by using material from an older temple.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rujivacharakul|first=Vimalin|url=https://books.google.co.id/books?id=FCoWAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA257&lpg=PA257&dq=Marijke+J.+Klokke+Gunung+Gangsir&source=bl&ots=dMqrQjddpr&sig=ACfU3U0mNre-edzLKvPwfi8iIsphm2NEMQ&hl=id&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwinmuCI5tXoAhWAIbcAHeOmDckQ6AEwAXoECAsQMw#v=onepage&q=Marijke%20J.%20Klokke%20Gunung%20Gangsir&f=false|title=Architecturalized Asia: Mapping a Continent through History|last2=Hahn|first2=H. Hazel|last3=Oshima|first3=Ken Tadashi|last4=Christensen|first4=Peter|date=2013-11-01|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-988-8208-05-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and design==\n[[File:036 View from South, Gunung Gangsir (39519447915).jpg|thumb|left|Gunung Gangsir temple viewed from the south.]]\nThe temple structure was made from red [[brick]]s, which is a common temple building materials in the region during [[Majapahit]] period (c. 14th  to 15th century), as demontrated by [[Pari Temple|Pari]] and [[Jabung]] temple nearby. However, the design, shape and proportion, also the decorations is more similar to Central Javanese temples from earlier period. The proportion for example, is quite similar to the 8th century [[Mendut]] temple near Borobudur.\n\nThe temple is facing East-Southeast direction, with a flight of stairs and portal facing that direction protruding on the east side of temple structure. The temple base is rectangular in shape with dimension of 15 metres x 15 metres. The temple is 15 metres in height, with visible distinction between foot (base) part, body, and roof. The elevated terrace and the room is about 5 metres in high from the ground, accessible through the stairs. Inside the temple, there is a spacious temple cella served as ''garbagriha'' or inner sanctum.<ref name=\"Perpusnas-Gangsir\"/> The roof is arranged in stepped pyramid arranged in three stages, the top stage and its pinnacle however is now missing.\n[[File:Candi Gunung Gangsir D.JPG|thumb|upright|Temple decorations of vessels with floral motif, made by clay mold casting technique.]]\nThe temple is quite richly decorated with niches, seams and decorated antifixes. Intricate panels, featuring ornaments in the form of bas-reliefs, vessels with floral motifs, pilasters, images of trees and animals, which are made with clay molding techniques. There are traces of plasters know as ''vajralepa'', which suggest originally the entire surface of the temple was covered with plaster, which is similar to the [[Kalasan]] and [[Sari temple]] near Prambanan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/886882212|title=Candi Indonesia|last=Sedyawati, Edi, 1938-|others=Latief, Feri, Indonesia. Direktorat Pelestarian Cagar Budaya dan Permuseuman,|isbn=9786021766934|edition=Cetakan pertama|lang=id|location=Jakarta|oclc=886882212}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pari Temple]]\n* [[Jawi Temple]]\n* [[Jabung]]\n* [[Trowulan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Candi Gunung Gangsir}}\n\n{{Hindu temples in Indonesia}}\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Indonesia|Gunung Gangsir]]\n[[Category:Kahuripan]]\n[[Category:Cultural Properties of Indonesia in East Java]]\n", "name_user": "Gunkarta", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunung_Gangsir"}
{"title_page": "Wajoq", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Wajo (disambiguation)}}\n{{under construction}}\n{{Infobox former country\n| native_name       = {{lang|bug|Akkarungeng ri Wajoq}}\n| conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Wajoq\n| common_name       = Wajoq\n| life_span         = c. 1400\u20131957\n| image_map         = \n| image_map_caption = \n| era               = [[Early modern]] to [[late modern]] periods\n| status            = Part of [[Dutch East Indies]] <small>(1906\u20131949)</small><br/>Part of [[Indonesia]] <small>(1949\u20131957)</small>\n| government_type   = [[Elective monarchy|Elective]] [[constitutional monarchy|constitutional]] [[monarchy]]{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=498}}\n| event_start       = Established\n| date_start        = early 15th century\n| event1            = [[South Sulawesi expeditions of 1905|Subjugated]] by the [[Dutch East Indies|Dutch colonial government]]\n| date_event1       = 1906\n| event_end         = Disestablished and transformed into a [[Regency (Indonesia)|regency]] of [[South Sulawesi]]\n| date_end          = 1957\n| p1                = Cinnotabiq\n| s1                = Wajo Regency\n| flag_s1           = \n| capital           = Tosora <small>(until 1906)</small><br/>[[Sengkang, Indonesia|S\u00e9ngkang]] <small>(1906\u20131957)</small>\n| common_languages  = [[Bugis , Bajo language|Bugis]]\n| today             = [[Indonesia]]\n}}\n\n'''Wajoq''', also spelled '''Wajo''', '''Bajo'''', or '''Wajok''',{{efn|The [[glottal stop]] in [[Bugis language|Bugis]] and other [[South Sulawesi languages]] is variously represented with \u27e8q\u27e9, \u27e8k\u27e9, \u27e8'\u27e9, or left unwritten. For consistency, this article follows the scheme used in {{harvtxt|Druce|2009}}, where \u27e8q\u27e9 is used for the glottal stop, \u27e8e\u27e9 represents a [[schwa]], and \u27e8\u00e9\u27e9 represents [e].}} was a [[Bugis people|Bugis]] elective principality in the western part of the [[South Sulawesi]] peninsula. It was founded in the 15th century, and reached its peak in the 18th century, when it briefly became the hegemon of South Sulawesi replacing [[Bone state|Bon\u00e9]]. Wajoq retained its independence until it was [[South Sulawesi expeditions of 1905|subdued in the early 20th century]] by the [[Dutch East Indies|Dutch colonial government]]. It continued to exist in some form up to mid-20th century, when the self-governing entity was transformed into [[Wajo Regency]] in the newly independent [[Republic of Indonesia]].\n\n== History ==\n=== Early history (c. 1400\u20131582) ===\nThe emergence of Wajoq and other interior polities of South Sulawesi is associated with the major [[intensive farming|agricultural expansion]] and [[centralized government|political centralization]] in the 14th century, which was encouraged by an increase in external demand for South Sulawesi rice.{{sfnp|Druce|2009|pp=34\u201336}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=100\u2013103}} Population rose as the formerly common [[Slash-and-burn|swidden]] agriculture was increasingly replaced with intensive [[wet rice]] cultivation. Throughout the interior of the peninsula, forests were [[deforestation|cleared]] and new settlements were founded.{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=98\u2013100}} The people of Wajoq themselves associate the origin of their polity with migrations and establishment of new settlements. Wajorese text ''[[Lontaraq Sukkuqna Wajoq]]'' (''Complete Chronicle of Wajoq''), for example, recounts the story of a Bugis noble who, on a hunting expedition, found \"an area with wide fields, thick forests with wild boars, deer, and buffalo, and numerous lakes replete with fish\".{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=27}} He then decided to settle and founded the polity of Cinnotabiq,{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|pp=348, 359}} which transformed into Wajoq in the early 15th century.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=24}}\n\nTradition mantains that the name \"Wajoq\" came from the ''bajoq'' tree{{efn|Commonly identified as a ''[[Macaranga]]'' species ({{harvnb|Abidin|1985|p=403}}).}}, under which the then Cinnotabiq ruler La Tenribali{{efn|Also known in several manuscripts as La Tenriba or La Tenribabbareng ({{harvnb|Abidin|1985|p=399}}).}} supposedly concluded a [[social contract]] with the three chiefs of Boliq, whose communities formed the core of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|pp=477\u2013478}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=25, 114}} La Tenribali was appointed to reign over Boliq lands and thus became the first ''batara'' (ruler, {{abbr|lit.|literally}} \"sky\") of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|pp=477\u2013478}} The third ''batara'' of Wajoq, La Pateddungi To Samallangiq, was forced to [[abdicate]] by his people, reportedly because of his immoral actions. He was later [[assassin]]ated by a Wajorese noble.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=478}} Wajoq then underwent a constitutional change, after which a governing council was established. This council included and was presided by an elective principal ruler, who from then on would be known as the ''arung matoa'' (lit. \"senior lord\"{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=174}}). La Pal\u00e9wo To Palippu from B\u00e9tt\u00e9mpola was chosen by the council as the first ''arung matoa'' of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|pp=479\u2013482}}\n\nDuring the reign of the fourth ''arung matoa'', [[La Tadampareq|La Tadampareq Puang ri Maggalatung]] ({{abbr|r.|reigned}} {{abbr|c.|circa}} 1491\u20131521{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=575}}), Wajoq became one of the major Bugis polities.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=28}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=112\u2013113}} By the turn of the 16th century, Wajoq had been able to secure a relatively higher standing in its relationship with the neighboring [[Luwu|Luwuq]], which was a powerful polity in South Sulawesi during the 15th century, and presumably was regarded as Wajoq's overlord.{{sfnp|Druce|2009|p=228}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=21}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=113\u2013114}} Together with Luwuq, Wajoq won a war against the nearby polity of [[Sidenreng|Sid\u00e9nr\u00e9ng]] in [[Ajatappareng]], forcing the latter to cede its territories north of the central lakes to Wajoq.{{sfnp|Druce|2009|p=228}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=113\u2013114}} Wajoq under La Tadampareq also absorbed the remnants of what might have been the core territories of Cina, another influential early Bugis polity.{{sfnp|Caldwell|Wellen|2017|pp=306, 319}} Balance of power in the region further shifted in the early 16th century when [[Bone state|Bon\u00e9]], a Bugis polity south of Wajoq, emerged victorious against Luwuq, and thus assumed a paramount position in the eastern part of the peninsula.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=28}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=22}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=114}} At the same time, the [[Makassar people|Makassar]] twin kingdoms of [[Sultanate of Gowa|Gowa]] and [[Kingdom of Tallo|Talloq]] to the west also [[Early history of Gowa and Talloq#Gowa and Talloq from 1511 to 1565|started to expand their power]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=24}} Early in the century, Gowa had cooperated with Bon\u00e9 in wars against Luwuq and Wajoq,{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=23}} but by the mid of the century their struggles for [[hegemony]] made Gowa and Bon\u00e9 clashed against each other. By this time, Wajoq had also fallen under Gowa's sphere of influence, and supported Gowa in a war against Bon\u00e9 in the 1560s.{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=116, 131\u2013132}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=30}}\n\n=== The ''Tellumpocco'' alliance and the rise of Gowa-Talloq (1582\u20131660) ===\n[[File:South Sulawesi circa 1600.svg|thumb|upright=1|Political division of southern Sulawesi in around 1590]]\n\nThe continued rise of Gowa and its harsh treatment of its Bugis subordinates Wajoq and [[Soppeng|Sopp\u00e9ng]] prompted the latter two to sign the Treaty of Timurung, a mutual defense pact initiated by Bon\u00e9 in 1582.{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=132\u2013133}} The relationship between these three allied Bugis polities, also known as the ''[[Tellumpocco]]'' (\"Three Powers\", lit. \"Three Peaks\"), is defined as that of brothers, with Bon\u00e9 acting as the elder, Wajoq the middle, and Sopp\u00e9ng the younger one. It sought to reclaim the autonomy of these Bugis lands, and to stop Gowa's expansionism.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=30\u201331}}{{sfnp|Druce|2009|p=249}} Gowa's subsequent campaigns against Wajoq in 1582 and 1590 as well as against Bon\u00e9 in 1585 and 1588 were all successfully repulsed by the alliance, or in the case of 1590 campaign, abandoned following the murder of Gowa's ruler [[Tunijalloq]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=31}}\n\nNevertheless, by the early 17th century, Gowa and Talloq had succeeded in becoming the most dominant powers in the South Sulawesi peninsula as they bolstered international trade and promoted the new faith of [[Islam]].{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=29, 177}} Between 1608 and 1611, Gowa waged successful campaigns throughout South Sulawesi, forcing Sopp\u00e9ng to embrace Islam in 1609, Wajoq in 1610, and Bon\u00e9 in 1611.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=33}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=136\u2013137}} Thereafter, the ''Tellumpocco'' surrendered the control of their foreign affairs to Gowa, although they were allowed to retain the alliance and still preserve considerable autonomy within their own domains.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37\u201338}} This arrangement proved to be quite successful to win the support of the Bugis. Wajoq in particular grew increasingly loyal to Gowa. The ''arung matoa'' To Mappassaungng\u00e9 (r. 1627\u20131628{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=576}}) even offered to guard the Gowa capital when its ruler was off for an expedition, despite he was not being obliged to do so.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37\u201338}}\n\nWajoq entered another conflict when the ruler of Bon\u00e9, [[La Maddaremmeng]] (r. 1626\u20131643), whether for political or religious reasons, attacked and pillaged P\u00e9n\u00e9ki, one of Wajoq's constituent communities.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=40}}{{efn|La Maddaremmeng had previously became a subject of controversy, as he had enforced a stricter interpretation of Islam to his people. He also went to abolish non-hereditary slavery in accordance to his belief, and tried to convince the other ''Tellumpocco'' members to follow his steps. This was not received favorably by Gowa, who viewed Bon\u00e9's attempt to spread its religious influence as a direct challenge to its hegemony over South Sulawesi ({{harvnb|Wellen|2014|p=29}}; {{harvnb|Andaya|1981|pp=39\u201340}}; {{harvnb|Pelras|1996|p=142}}).}} As La Maddaremmeng refused to compensate for the goods seized in P\u00e9n\u00e9ki, Wajoq and Bon\u00e9 went to war against each other.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}} Gowa and Sopp\u00e9ng sided with Wajoq in this conflict, and the joint forces succeeded in [[Battle of Passemp\u00e9|defeating Bon\u00e9 in October 1643]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=39\u201340}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=142}} Bon\u00e9 was harshly punished by being made a vassal of Gowa,{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}} with a Bugis noble installed as a [[regent]] responsible to a Makassar lord. A subsequent rebellion led by La Maddaremmeng's brother was also quashed, and Bon\u00e9's status was further degraded to that of a \"slave\" (i.e. a colony), while its nobles were forcibly relocated to Gowa.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=41\u201342}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=142\u2013143}} Several contested territories held by Bon\u00e9 were given to Wajoq, and a large number of people from Bon\u00e9 were forced into [[Corv\u00e9e|unpaid labor]] in Wajoq.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=29\u201330}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=42\u201343}} This humiliation entrenched a feeling of resentment among the people of Bon\u00e9 towards both Gowa and Wajoq.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=30}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=43}}\n\n=== Makassar War and Wajorese migrations (1660\u20131730) ===\nBy the second quarter of the 17th century, Gowa and Talloq had became the most politically and economically powerful polities in eastern Indonesia. The twin kingdoms' attempt to retain their hegemony brought them to a conflict with the [[Dutch East India Company]] (VOC), which wanted to monopolize the [[spice trade]] in the [[Moluccas]].{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=30}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=45\u201347}} In 1660, the Dutch attacked Gowa and managed to seize the fort of Paqnakkukang.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=49}} Gowa then forced its vassals to provide labor to build military constructions in anticipation of further conflict, which ultimately resulted in a rebellion led by the Bon\u00e9 noble [[Arung Palakka]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=50\u201352}} However, his attempt to revive the ''Tellumpocco'' alliance failed, as Wajoq refused to break its treaty with Gowa to join forces with the rebels.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=30}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=54}}<!-- According to the historian [[Leonard Andaya]], Wajoq's decision can be explained by the fact that its recent experiences with Gowa were much more positive than those with Bon\u00e9.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=54\u201355}} In the most recent memory of the Wajorese, it was Bon\u00e9, not Gowa, which invaded their country. Wajoq and Bon\u00e9 also had frequent disputes over territorial boundaries and the allegiance of their vassals.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=54\u201355}}{{efn|system of vassals...}} On the other hand, Wajoq's relationship with Gowa had been more friendly in the preceding years; Wajoq was one of Gowa's most trusted vassals, with the ''arung matoa'' [[La Tenrilai To Senngeng]] (r. 1658\u20131670) had even been married to a daughter of Gowa ruler [[Hasanuddin of Gowa|Hasanuddin]] (r. 1653\u20131669).{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37, 54\u201355}}--> Lacking enough support, the rebellion was successfully quelled by Gowa and Wajoq forces, driving Arung Palakka to escape to [[Buton]], and later, to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]], seeking aid from the VOC.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=56\u201359, 66}}\n\nDuring the [[Makassar War]] (1666\u20131669), Wajoq fiercely supported Gowa against the alliance of the VOC and local forces from Bon\u00e9 and elsewhere led by Arung Palakka. Even after the fall of Gowa's court Sombaopu and the formal surrender of Gowa and Talloq, the ''arung matoa'' [[La Tenrilai To Sengngeng]] (r. 1658\u20131670) still refused to abide by the [[Treaty of Bungaya]] and continued to resist the Dutch and Bon\u00e9 forces.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=31\u201332}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37, 124\u2013126, 138}} By mid-1670, Arung Palakka had launched a large-scale invasion of Wajoq.<!-- Along the way, several Wajoq's vassals deserted and joined Bon\u00e9 forces, bringing the total number of invading forces to around 40,000 people when it arrived to besiege Tosora, the walled capital city of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=138\u2013139}}--> Despite hard resistance from Wajorese defenders, the walled capital city of Tosora fell to the Bon\u00e9-led forces in December 1670. La Tenrilai was [[killed in action]], and his successor [[La Paliliq To Malu]] (r. 1670\u20131679) was forced to sign a treaty restricting Wajorese political, trade and military powers, in addition to the Treaty of Bungaya.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=33\u201335}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=140\u2013141}} In spite of Wajoq's surrender, it still faced harsh retribution from Arung Palakka and the people of Bon\u00e9. Many Wajorese were kidnapped and harassed or had their belongings seized.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=36}} Bon\u00e9 also annexed the coastal territories near the mouth of [[Walanae River|Cenrana River]], which was Wajoq's sole acess to the sea.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=143}} Wajoq's complains to the Dutch at Makassar regarding Bon\u00e9's arbitrary actions were given little attention. By this time, Arung Palakka had been sending soldiers to help the VOC in [[Trunajaya rebellion|a campaign in Java]], and the VOC did not want to risk severing their relationship with an important ally.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=37\u201338}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=142\u2013143, 190\u2013192, 205}}\n\nIt was these difficulties faced by the Wajorese in their homeland which prompted them to emigrate elsewhere.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=143}} While migration had always been an important part of Wajorese culture, it was particularly prominent in the aftermath of the Makassar War, when a large number of Wajorese migrants established themselves abroad in Makassar, eastern [[Borneo]], the [[Lesser Sunda Islands]], and the [[Straits of Malacca]] area, among other places.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=143}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=38, 82}}{{sfnp|Lineton|1975b|p=178}} These diaspora communities were connected to their homeland as well as to each other by familial, commercial, political and legal ties.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82}} By the early 18th century, a sequence of Wajorese rulers had begun to take advantage of these connections to revitalize their country. Several rulers ordered their people abroad to buy weapons to rearm Wajoq.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82}}{{sfnp|Duli|2010|pp=144\u2013145}} Attention was also given to commerce; one particular ''arung matoa'', [[La Tenriwerrung Puanna Sangngaji]] (r. 1711\u20131713), even proclaimed it as a moral duty, noting that the people of Wajoq \"could not 'stand upright' unless they sought riches\".{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82}} His successor, [[La Sal\u00e9wangeng To Tenrirua]] (r. 1713\u20131736), actively supported international commerce in more practical ways.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=82\u201383}} He dredged the river that leads to the capital Tosora to ease access for large boats, strengthened local industries by requiring them to appoint political representatives known as ''akkajenangngeng'', created an official governmental post with the specific role of promoting trade, and set up a fund which can be used for investment on commerce and agriculture as well as for social security purposes.{{sfnp|Duli|2010|pp=144\u2013145}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=82\u201383}}\n\n=== Wajoq under La Maddukelleng (1730\u20131754) ===\n{{sect-stub|date=April 2020}}\nSince Arung Palakka's death in 1696, none of his successor was as capable as him in maintaining Bon\u00e9's hegemony over South Sulawesi. This allowed Wajorese trade to flourish without much restriction.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=30, 69}} Interaction between Wajorese diaspora communities and their homeland intensified, and it culminated in the 1730s when the exiled Wajorese [[La Maddukelleng]] came back to South Sulawesi.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=137}} At first, he and his followers raided several communities in the western part of the peninsula and in the islands near Makassar.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=55}} In 1736, he assumed the leadership of P\u00e9n\u00e9ki (a constituent polity of Wajoq) and got involved in a confrontation with Bon\u00e9. Following a retaliatory invasion from Bon\u00e9, many Wajorese people came to support La Maddukelleng, and he assumed the position of ''arung matoa'' (r. 1736\u20131754{{efn|{{harvtxt|Noorduyn|1972|p=61}} dates his reign to 1737\u20131754, but according to {{harvtxt|Abidin|1985|p=577}} and {{harvtxt|Wellen|2014|p=145}}, he was appointed as the ''arung matoa'' of Wajoq on November 6, 1736. Wajorese sources recount that La Maddukelleng was chosen to replace La Sal\u00e9wangeng (who is reported to have voluntarily resigned), although several contemporary records indicated that he assumed the position through usurpation ({{harvnb|Wellen|2018|p=56}}).}}) not long after.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=56}} With popular support, he led Wajoq into victory over Bon\u00e9.{{sfnp|Noorduyn|1972|p=61}} By mid-1737 a peace agreement had been signed, and Bon\u00e9 was obliged to compensate for all the losses Wajoq had suffered under the rulers of Bon\u00e9 since the Makassar War.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=57}} Liberated from Bon\u00e9 dominance, Wajoq assumed a hegemonic position in South Sulawesi,{{sfnp|Noorduyn|1972|p=61}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=137, 158\u2013159}} with Wajorese record even stating that Wajoq was recognized as the leader of the ''Tellumpocco'' at the time.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=57}}\n<!--\nThe change in the balance of power in South Sulawesi concerned the Dutch, since Bon\u00e9 was their only ally in the region. La Maddukelleng attacked Dutch... retaliation...\n\n===1754\u20131957===\n\n-  19th century... expedition in South Sulawesi early 20th century... constitutionally made part of Indonesia in the late 50s.\n-->\n==Government and politics==\n{| class=\"me collapsible\" width=\"300\" style=\"float: right; clear: right; margin: 0 0 1em 1em; font-family: arial; font-size: 90%; border: 1px solid #cccccc\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: #e7dcc3\" | List of rulers{{efn|Adapted from {{harvtxt|Abidin|1985|pp=574\u2013578}}. Dates of reign for the first three rulers are not specified.}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: #99CCCC\" | ''Batara'' of Wajoq\n|-\n| La Tenribali\n|\n|-\n| La Mataesso\n|\n|-\n| La Pateddungi To Samallangiq\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: #99CCCC\" | ''Arung Matoa'' of Wajoq\n|-\n| La Pal\u00e9wo To Palippu\n| (1474\u20131481)\n|-\n| La Obbi Settiriwareq\n| (1481\u20131486)\n|-\n| La Tenritumpuq To Langiq\n| (1486\u20131481)\n|-\n| La Tadampareq Puang ri Maggalatung\n| (1491\u20131521)\n|-\n| La Tenripakado To Namp\u00e9\n| (1524\u20131535)\n|-\n| La Temassong\u00e9\n| (1535\u20131538)\n|-\n| La Warani To Temmagiang\n| (1538\u20131547)\n|-\n| La Mallageni\n| (1547)\n|-\n| La Mappapuli To Appademmeng\n| (1547\u20131564)\n|-\n| La Pakoko To Pabb\u00e9leq\n| (1564\u20131567)\n|-\n| La Mungkaceq To Uddamang\n| (1567\u20131607)\n|-\n| La Sangkuru Patauq Mulajaji\n| (1607\u20131610)\n|-\n| La Mappepulu To Appamol\u00e9\n| (1612\u20131616)\n|-\n| La Samal\u00e9wa To Appakiung\n| (1616\u20131621)\n|-\n| La Pakallongi To Alinrungi\n| (1621\u20131626)\n|-\n| To Mappassaungng\u00e9\n| (1627\u20131628)\n|-\n| La Pakallongi To Alinrungi\n| (1628\u20131636)\n|-\n| La Tenrilai To Uddamang\n| (1636\u20131639)\n|-\n| La Sigajang To Bunne\n| (1639\u20131643)\n|-\n| La Makkaraka To Patemmui\n| (1643\u20131648)\n|-\n| La Temmassongeq Puanna Da\u00e9li\n| (1648\u20131651)\n|-\n| La Parammaq To R\u00e9wo\n| (1651\u20131658)\n|-\n| La Tenrilai To Sengngeng\n| (1658\u20131670)\n|-\n| La Paliliq To Malu\n| (1670\u20131679)\n|-\n| La Pariusi Da\u00e9ng Manyampaq\n| (1679\u20131699)\n|-\n| La Tenrisessu To Timo\u00e9\n| (1699\u20131702)\n|-\n| La Mattoneq To Sakkeq\n| (1702\u20131703)\n|-\n| La Galigo To Sunia\n| (1703\u20131712)\n|-\n| La Tenriwerrung Puanna Sangngaji\n| (1712\u20131715)\n|-\n| La Sal\u00e9wangeng To Tenrirua\n| (1715\u20131736)\n|-\n| La Maddukelleng\n| (1736\u20131754)\n|-\n| La Maddanaca\n| (1754\u20131755)\n|-\n| La Passaung Puanna La Omoq\n| (1758\u20131761)\n|-\n| La Mappajung Puanna Salowo\n| (1761\u20131767)\n|-\n| La Malliungeng To All\u00e9ong\n| (1767\u20131770)\n|-\n| La Mallalengeng\n| (1795\u20131817)\n|-\n| La Manang To Appamadeng\n| (1821\u20131825)\n|-\n| La Paddengngeng Puanna Pallaguna\n| (1839\u20131845)\n|-\n| La Pawellangi Pajump\u00e9ro\u00e9\n| (1854\u20131859)\n|-\n| La Cincing Akil Ali\n| (1859\u20131885)\n|-\n| La Koro\n| (1885\u20131891)\n|-\n| La Passamulaq\n| (1892\u20131897)\n|-\n| Ishak Manggabarani\n| (1900\u20131916)\n|-\n| La Tenrioddang\n| (1926\u20131933)\n|-\n| Andiq Mangkonaq\n| (1933\u20131949)\n|}\n\nAs with many other Bugis states, Wajoq was a confederation of smaller political and territorial communities. These communities were related to each other as well as to the central government at Tosora in various ways, ranging from vassalage to alliance \"as between brothers\".{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=176\u2013177}} The polity of Wajoq was divided into three ''limpo'' or main districts, namely B\u00e9tt\u00e9mpola, Tua, and Talotenreng, which represented its three original founding communities.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|pp=49\u201350}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=177\u2013178}} Each ''limpo'' held power over several smaller communities that either chose to affiliate themselves with the said ''limpo'' or were conquered.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=50}} Each of these communities had considerable freedom, with its own leader and customs. It can also switch allegiance between different states, and by doing so, both its people and its territory will be subject to the new state.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=22}}\n\nThe paramount ruler of Wajoq was titled ''arung matoa''.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=23}} In running the day-to-day administration of Wajoq, the ''arung matoa'' was assisted by three pairs of civilian and military leaders, each pair representing one of the three ''limpo''.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=482}}{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=245}} The civilian leader of a ''limpo'' was called a ''ranreng'' or regent, while the military leader was called a ''bat\u00e9 lompo'' or \"standard bearer\".{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=178}} The titles of the ''bat\u00e9 lompo'' were taken from the banner they carried: ''Pilla'' or \"Scarlet\" for B\u00e9tt\u00e9mpola, ''Patola'' or \"Multi-colored\" for Talotenreng, and ''Cakkuridi'' or \"Yellow\" for Tua.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=23}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=485}} Each of the ''ranreng'' and  ''bat\u00e9 lompo'' were at least as powerful as the ''arung matoa''; together, these seven officials formed the state's highest governing body, known as ''Petta Wajoq''.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=23}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=178}}\n\nThe ''arung matoa'' was chosen among the \"white-blood\" or nobility class. The position of arung matoa cannot be held at once with another office. It also cannot be inherited and can only be held for life as long as the ruler was deemed fit for the position.{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|pp=465, 535}} A ruler in precolonial South Sulawesi was expected to be subordinate to the state and the ''[[adat]]'' or customary law which delineates the autonomy of local communities; failure to do so may result in removal from office. The ''arung matoa'' La Samal\u00e9wa To Appakiung (r. 1612\u20131616), for example, was deposed by his people, reportedly because of his arbitrary actions.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=22}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=385}}\n\nThe central governing council of Wajoq consisted of 40 officials, collectively called the ''Arung Patampulu'' (lit. \"Forty Lords\"{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=165}}), of which the ''arung matoa'' was a member as well as the head.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=482}} The whole members only convened on certain occasions, including the election of a new ''arung matoa''.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=23, 175}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=51}} The power of ''Arung Patampulu'', in turn, was balanced by three non-noble officials known as ''punggawa'', who were elected among the elders of each district.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=482}}{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=245}} These ''punggawa'' had considerable power. According to Brooke:{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=245}}\n\n{{quote\n|text=The powers of these pangawas [sic], or tribunes of the people, is considerable. With them only it rests to summon a meeting of the council of forty. They possess the right of veto to the appointment of an aru matoah [sic]. Their command alone is a legal summons to war, no chief or body having right, or even authority, to call the freemen to the field.\n|author=James Brooke\n}}\n\nIn addition to having ''punggawa'' as the formal permanent representation in the government, \"respectable\" commoners and village heads were also entitled to participate in the occasional extraordinary deliberative assembly which might be held in case the ''Arung Patampulu'' could not agree on the best way to resolve certain issues. These commoners may discuss and give input to the government on the best way to resolve these issues, although the ultimate decision in this kind of situations rested in the hands of ''arung matoa''.{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=246}}\n<!--\n- Diaspora governmental structure (focus on Borneo and Makassar)...\n-->\n\n==Culture and society==\n{{see also|Bugis people}}\n{{sect-stub|date=April 2020}}\nWajorese texts often reiterate that \"the people of Wajoq are free\", and that their only master is the customary law, which is based on consensus. The concept of the \"freedoms of Wajoq\" included, among others: [[freedom of speech|freedom of expressing opinions]], freedom to act based on one's intention, [[freedom of movement]], [[freedom of contract]], and the freedom from unjust punishment.{{sfnp|Reid|1998|p=148}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=481}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|pp=433, 447\u2013448}} These \"freedoms\", however, had limitations and do not necessarily apply to the whole population.\n\nBugis women in the precolonial states of South Sulawesi were routinely involved in many aspects of the society. Women were also actively involved in the government. One 19th-century observer states that the women of South Sulawesi were commonly \"consulted by the men on all public affairs\" and were often \"raised to the throne, [even] when the monarchy is elective\".{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=250}} The British adventurer [[James Brooke]] (future [[Rajah of Sarawak]]), notes that at the time of his visit to Wajoq in 1840, four out of six members of Petta Ennengng\u00e9 were women, who frequently \"appear in public like the men; ride, rule, and visit even foreigners, without the knowledge or consent of their husbands.\"{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=250}}\n\n==Economy==\nWajoq was the source of most South Sulawesi overseas merchants between late 17th and late 19th centuries.{{sfnp|Reid|1998|p=147}} Wajorese commerce extended as far as [[Sumatra]], [[Cambodia]], and [[New Guinea]].{{sfnp|Lineton|1975b|p=178}}{{sfnp|Reid|1998|p=147}} Throughout the Maritime Southeast Asia, Wajorese and other Bugis merchants acted as intermediaries between large and small trading nations.{{sfnp|Lineton|1975b|p=178}} Wajorese trade flourished in part because of deliberate support from the government at Wajoq as well as from Wajorese communities abroad.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=67\u201368}} Leaders of Wajorese overseas communities regularly convened to advance their interest. One such conference in the early 18th century saw the codification of laws regulating Wajorese commerce and navigation, popularly called the Ammana Gappa's law code, after the then leader of the Wajorese community in Makassar. These laws set up frameworks for managing credit and debts as well as regulating other kinds of business relationships, providing ways to resolve conflict and giving Wajorese merchants advantages over merchants from other groups in Maritime Southeast Asia.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=84, 91, 97}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=64\u201365, 71}} Such a law code, according to historian Kathryn Wellen, is \"highly unusual, if not unique, for early modern insular Southeast Asia\".{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=84}}\n\nThe government financially supported Wajorese merchants by providing monetary loans, taken from the fund established by La Sal\u00e9wangeng. Borrowers were obliged to return the principals alongside parts of their profits. The profits would then be used to further Wajoq's interest, such as building armaments or renovating the state's mosque. This system allowed a large segment of Wajorese population to participate in commerce while also utilizing their economic power for the benefit of the society as a whole.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82\u201383, 97}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=76}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Early history of Gowa and Talloq]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Abidin |first=Andi Zainal |year=1983 |title=The emergence of early kingdoms in South Sulawesi: A preliminary remark on governmental contracts from the thirteenth to the fifteenth century |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/32159714 |journal=Southeast Asian Studies |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=455\u2013491 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Abidin |first=Andi Zainal |author-mask=3 |year=1985 |title=Wajo\u2019 pada Abad XV\u2013XVI: Suatu Penggalian Sejarah Terpendam Sulawesi Selatan dari Lontara |trans-title=Wajo' in the XV\u2013XVI Centuries: An Exploration of South Sulawesi's Forgotten History from Lontara Texts |lang=Indonesian |location=Bandung |publisher=Penerbit Alumni |oclc=12901929 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Ammarell |first=Gene |year=2002 |title=Bugis migration and modes of adaptation to local situations |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4153020 |journal=Ethnology |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=51\u201367 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Andaya |first=Leonard Y. |authorlink=Leonard Andaya |year=1981 |title=The Heritage of Arung Palakka: A History of South Sulawesi (Celebes) in the Seventeenth Century |url=https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=to5uAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions:E-DwSVS6BfQC |location=Ann Arbor |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=9789024724635 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last1=Caldwell |first1=Ian |last2=Wellen |first2=Kathryn Anderson |year=2017 |title=Finding Cina: A new paradigm for early Bugis history |url=https://brill.com/view/journals/bki/173/2-3/article-p296_6.xml |journal=[[Bijdragen tot de Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde]] |volume=173 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=296\u2013324 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Duli |first=Akin |year=2010 |title=Peranan Tosora sebagai pusat pemerintahan Kerajaan Wajo abad XVI\u2013XIX |trans-title=The role of Tosora as the political center of the Kingdom of Wajo in the XVI\u2013XIX centuries |lang=Indonesian |url=http://walennae.kemdikbud.go.id/index.php/walennae/article/view/237 |journal=Walennae |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=143\u2013158 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Druce |first=Stephen C. |year=2009 |title=The Lands West of the Lakes: A History of the Ajattappareng Kingdoms of South Sulawesi, 1200 to 1600 CE |url=https://books.google.com/?id=HfNjAAAAQBAJ |location=Leiden |publisher=Brill |isbn=9789004253827 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=H\u00e4gerdal |first=Hans |year=2015 |title=The Open Door: Early Modern Wajorese Statecraft and Diaspora (review) |url= |journal=HumaNetten |volume=35 |pages=50\u201352 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last1=Henley |first1=David |last2=Caldwell |first2=Ian |year=2019 |title=Precolonial citizenship in South Sulawesi |journal=Citizenship Studies |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/13621025.2019.1603271 |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=240\u2013255 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite thesis |last=Lineton |first=Jacqueline |year=1975a |title=An Indonesian society and its universe: A study of the Bugis of South Sulawesi (Celebes) and their role within a wider social and economic system |type=PhD dissertation |location=London |publisher=School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Lineton |first=Jacqueline |author-mask=3 |year=1975b |title=Pasompe\u2019 Ugi\u2019: Bugis migrants and wanderers |url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/arch_0044-8613_1975_num_10_1_1248 |journal=Archipel |volume=10 |pages=173\u2013201 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Noorduyn |first=Jacobus |year=1972 |title=Arung Singkang (1700-1765): How the victory of Wadjo\u2019 began |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3350682 |journal=Indonesia |volume=13 |pages=61\u201368 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Noorduyn |first=Jacobus |author-mask=3 |year=2000 |title=The Wajorese merchants community in Makassar |url=https://brill.com/view/journals/bki/156/3/article-p473_5.xml |journal=Bijdragen tot de Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde |volume=156 |issue=3 |pages=473\u2013498 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Patunru |first=Abdurrazak Daeng |year=1983 |title=Sejarah Wajo |trans-title=The History of Wajo |lang=Indonesian |location=Ujung Pandang |publisher=Yayasan Kebudayaan Sulawesi Selatan |oclc=215821862 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Pelras |first=Christian |authorlink=Christian Pelras |year=1971a |title=Hi\u00e9rarchie et pouvoir traditionnels en pays Wadjo' |trans-title=Traditional hierarchy and power in the country of Wadjo' |lang=French |url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/arch_0044-8613_1971_num_1_1_930 |journal=Archipel |volume=1 |pages=169\u2013191 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Pelras |first=Christian |author-mask=3 |year=1971b |title=Hi\u00e9rarchie et pouvoir traditionnels en pays Wadjo' (suite et fin) |trans-title=Traditional hierarchy and power in the country of Wadjo' (end) |lang=French|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/arch_0044-8613_1971_num_2_1_965 |journal=Archipel |volume=2 |pages=197\u2013223 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Pelras |first=Christian |author-mask=3 |year=1993 |title=Religion, tradition and the dynamics of Islamization in South-Sulawesi |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3351245 |journal=Indonesia |volume=57 |issue=1 |pages=133\u2013154 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Pelras |first=Christian |author-mask=3 |year=1996 |title=The Bugis |location=Oxford |publisher=Blackwell Publishers |isbn=9780631172314 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Reid |first=Anthony |authorlink=Anthony Reid |year=1993 |title=Southeast Asia in the Age of Commerce, 1450-1680: Expansion and crisis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxgHExnla4MC |location=New Haven |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=9780300054125}}p.48 on undang undang laut and amanna gappa\n: {{cite book |last=Reid |first=Anthony |author-mask=3 |year=1998 |chapter=Merdeka: The Concept of Freedom in Indonesia |editor1=David Kelly |editor2=Anthony Reid |title=Asian Freedoms: The Idea of Freedom in East and Southeast Asia |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521637572 |pages=141\u2013160 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Reid |first=Anthony |author-mask=3 |year=2016 |title=The Open Door: Early Modern Wajorese Statecraft and Diaspora (review) |url= |journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=312\u2013315 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Wellen |first=Kathryn Anderson |year=2009 |chapter=Credit among the Early Modern To Wajoq |editor1=David Henley |editor2=Peter Boomgaard |title=Credit and Debit in Indonesia:  From Peonage to Pawnshop, from Kongsi to Cooperative |location=Leiden |publisher=KITLV Press |isbn=9789067183505 |pages=102\u2013123 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Wellen |first=Kathryn Anderson |author-mask=3 |year=2014 |title=The Open Door: Early Modern Wajorese Statecraft and Diaspora |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jU70gPq6eZIC |location=DeKalb |publisher=Northern Illinois University Press |isbn=9780875807126 |ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=Wellen |first=Kathryn Anderson |author-mask=3 |year=2018 |chapter=La Maddukelleng and Civil War in South Sulawesi |editor1=Michael Charney |editor2=Kathryn Wellen |title=Warring societies of pre-colonial Southeast Asia: Local cultures of conflict within a regional context |series=Studies on Asian topics |volume=62 |location=Kopenhagen |publisher=NIAS Press |isbn=9788776942281 |pages=47\u201371 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Precolonial states in Indonesia}}\n\n[[Category:Precolonial states of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:History of Sulawesi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Wajo (disambiguation)}}\n{{under construction}}\n{{Infobox former country\n| native_name       = {{lang|bug|Akkarungeng ri Wajoq}}\n| conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Wajoq\n| common_name       = Wajoq\n| life_span         = c. 1400\u20131957\n| image_map         = \n| image_map_caption = \n| era               = [[Early modern]] to [[late modern]] periods\n| status            = Part of [[Dutch East Indies]] <small>(1906\u20131949)</small><br/>Part of [[Indonesia]] <small>(1949\u20131957)</small>\n| government_type   = [[Elective monarchy|Elective]] [[constitutional monarchy|constitutional]] [[monarchy]]{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=498}}\n| event_start       = Established\n| date_start        = early 15th century\n| event1            = [[South Sulawesi expeditions of 1905|Subjugated]] by the [[Dutch East Indies|Dutch colonial government]]\n| date_event1       = 1906\n| event_end         = Disestablished and transformed into a [[Regency (Indonesia)|regency]] of [[South Sulawesi]]\n| date_end          = 1957\n| p1                = Cinnotabiq\n| s1                = Wajo Regency\n| flag_s1           = \n| capital           = Tosora <small>(until 1906)</small><br/>[[Sengkang, Indonesia|S\u00e9ngkang]] <small>(1906\u20131957)</small>\n| common_languages  = [[Bugis , Bajo language|Bugis]]\n| today             = [[Indonesia]]\n}}\n\n'''Wajoq''', also spelled '''Wajo''', '''Bajo'''', or '''Wajok''',{{efn|The [[glottal stop]] in [[Bugis language|Bugis]] and other [[South Sulawesi languages]] is variously represented with \u27e8q\u27e9, \u27e8k\u27e9, \u27e8'\u27e9, or left unwritten. For consistency, this article follows the scheme used in {{harvtxt|Druce|2009}}, where \u27e8q\u27e9 is used for the glottal stop, \u27e8e\u27e9 represents a [[schwa]], and \u27e8\u00e9\u27e9 represents [e].}} was a [[Bugis people|Bugis]] elective principality in the western part of the [[South Sulawesi]] peninsula. It was founded in the 15th century, and reached its peak in the 18th century, when it briefly became the hegemon of South Sulawesi replacing [[Bone state|Bon\u00e9]]. Wajoq retained its independence until it was [[South Sulawesi expeditions of 1905|subdued in the early 20th century]] by the [[Dutch East Indies|Dutch colonial government]]. It continued to exist in some form up to mid-20th century, when the self-governing entity was transformed into [[Wajo Regency]] in the newly independent [[Republic of Indonesia]].\n\n== History ==\n=== Early history (c. 1400\u20131582) ===\nThe emergence of Wajoq and other interior polities of South Sulawesi is associated with the major [[intensive farming|agricultural expansion]] and [[centralized government|political centralization]] in the 14th century, which was encouraged by an increase in external demand for South Sulawesi rice.{{sfnp|Druce|2009|pp=34\u201336}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=100\u2013103}} Population rose as the formerly common [[Slash-and-burn|swidden]] agriculture was increasingly replaced with intensive [[wet rice]] cultivation. Throughout the interior of the peninsula, forests were [[deforestation|cleared]] and new settlements were founded.{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=98\u2013100}} The people of Wajoq themselves associate the origin of their polity with migrations and establishment of new settlements. Wajorese text ''[[Lontaraq Sukkuqna Wajoq]]'' (''Complete Chronicle of Wajoq''), for example, recounts the story of a Bugis noble who, on a hunting expedition, found \"an area with wide fields, thick forests with wild boars, deer, and buffalo, and numerous lakes replete with fish\".{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=27}} He then decided to settle and founded the polity of Cinnotabiq,{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|pp=348, 359}} which transformed into Wajoq in the early 15th century.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=24}}\n\nTradition mantains that the name \"Wajoq\" came from the ''bajoq'' tree{{efn|Commonly identified as a ''[[Macaranga]]'' species ({{harvnb|Abidin|1985|p=403}}).}}, under which the then Cinnotabiq ruler La Tenribali{{efn|Also known in several manuscripts as La Tenriba or La Tenribabbareng ({{harvnb|Abidin|1985|p=399}}).}} supposedly concluded a [[social contract]] with the three chiefs of Boliq, whose communities formed the core of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|pp=477\u2013478}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=25, 114}} La Tenribali was appointed to reign over Boliq lands and thus became the first ''batara'' (ruler, {{abbr|lit.|literally}} \"sky\") of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|pp=477\u2013478}} The third ''batara'' of Wajoq, La Pateddungi To Samallangiq, was forced to [[abdicate]] by his people, reportedly because of his immoral actions. He was later [[assassin]]ated by a Wajorese noble.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=478}} Wajoq then underwent a constitutional change, after which a governing council was established. This council included and was presided by an elective principal ruler, who from then on would be known as the ''arung matoa'' (lit. \"senior lord\"{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=174}}). La Pal\u00e9wo To Palippu from B\u00e9tt\u00e9mpola was chosen by the council as the first ''arung matoa'' of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|pp=479\u2013482}}\n\nDuring the reign of the fourth ''arung matoa'', [[La Tadampareq|La Tadampareq Puang ri Maggalatung]] ({{abbr|r.|reigned}} {{abbr|c.|circa}} 1491\u20131521{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=575}}), Wajoq became one of the major Bugis polities.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=28}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=112\u2013113}} By the turn of the 16th century, Wajoq had been able to secure a relatively higher standing in its relationship with the neighboring [[Luwu|Luwuq]], which was a powerful polity in South Sulawesi during the 15th century, and presumably was regarded as Wajoq's overlord.{{sfnp|Druce|2009|p=228}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=21}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=113\u2013114}} Together with Luwuq, Wajoq won a war against the nearby polity of [[Sidenreng|Sid\u00e9nr\u00e9ng]] in [[Ajatappareng]], forcing the latter to cede its territories north of the central lakes to Wajoq.{{sfnp|Druce|2009|p=228}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=113\u2013114}} Wajoq under La Tadampareq also absorbed the remnants of what might have been the core territories of Cina, another influential early Bugis polity.{{sfnp|Caldwell|Wellen|2017|pp=306, 319}} Balance of power in the region further shifted in the early 16th century when [[Bone state|Bon\u00e9]], a Bugis polity south of Wajoq, emerged victorious against Luwuq, and thus assumed a paramount position in the eastern part of the peninsula.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=28}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=22}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=114}} At the same time, the [[Makassar people|Makassar]] twin kingdoms of [[Sultanate of Gowa|Gowa]] and [[Kingdom of Tallo|Talloq]] to the west also [[Early history of Gowa and Talloq#Gowa and Talloq from 1511 to 1565|started to expand their power]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=24}} Early in the century, Gowa had cooperated with Bon\u00e9 in wars against Luwuq and Wajoq,{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=23}} but by the mid of the century their struggles for [[hegemony]] made Gowa and Bon\u00e9 clashed against each other. By this time, Wajoq had also fallen under Gowa's sphere of influence, and supported Gowa in a war against Bon\u00e9 in the 1560s.{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=116, 131\u2013132}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=30}}\n\n=== The ''Tellumpocco'' alliance and the rise of Gowa-Talloq (1582\u20131660) ===\n[[File:South Sulawesi circa 1600.svg|thumb|upright=1|Political division of southern Sulawesi in around 1590]]\n\nThe continued rise of Gowa and its harsh treatment of its Bugis subordinates Wajoq and [[Soppeng|Sopp\u00e9ng]] prompted the latter two to sign the Treaty of Timurung, a mutual defense pact initiated by Bon\u00e9 in 1582.{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=132\u2013133}} The relationship between these three allied Bugis polities, also known as the ''[[Tellumpocco]]'' (\"Three Powers\", lit. \"Three Peaks\"), is defined as that of brothers, with Bon\u00e9 acting as the elder, Wajoq the middle, and Sopp\u00e9ng the younger one. It sought to reclaim the autonomy of these Bugis lands, and to stop Gowa's expansionism.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=30\u201331}}{{sfnp|Druce|2009|p=249}} Gowa's subsequent campaigns against Wajoq in 1582 and 1590 as well as against Bon\u00e9 in 1585 and 1588 were all successfully repulsed by the alliance, or in the case of 1590 campaign, abandoned following the murder of Gowa's ruler [[Tunijalloq]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=31}}\n\nNevertheless, by the early 17th century, Gowa and Talloq had succeeded in becoming the most dominant powers in the South Sulawesi peninsula as they bolstered international trade and promoted the new faith of [[Islam]].{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=29, 177}} Between 1608 and 1611, Gowa waged successful campaigns throughout South Sulawesi, forcing Sopp\u00e9ng to embrace Islam in 1609, Wajoq in 1610, and Bon\u00e9 in 1611.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=33}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=136\u2013137}} Thereafter, the ''Tellumpocco'' surrendered the control of their foreign affairs to Gowa, although they were allowed to retain the alliance and still preserve considerable autonomy within their own domains.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37\u201338}} This arrangement proved to be quite successful to win the support of the Bugis. Wajoq in particular grew increasingly loyal to Gowa. The ''arung matoa'' To Mappassaungng\u00e9 (r. 1627\u20131628{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=576}}) even offered to guard the Gowa capital when its ruler was off for an expedition, despite he was not being obliged to do so.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37\u201338}}\n\nWajoq entered another conflict when the ruler of Bon\u00e9, [[La Maddaremmeng]] (r. 1626\u20131643), whether for political or religious reasons, attacked and pillaged P\u00e9n\u00e9ki, one of Wajoq's constituent communities.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=40}}{{efn|La Maddaremmeng had previously became a subject of controversy, as he had enforced a stricter interpretation of Islam to his people. He also went to abolish non-hereditary slavery in accordance to his belief, and tried to convince the other ''Tellumpocco'' members to follow his steps. This was not received favorably by Gowa, who viewed Bon\u00e9's attempt to spread its religious influence as a direct challenge to its hegemony over South Sulawesi ({{harvnb|Wellen|2014|p=29}}; {{harvnb|Andaya|1981|pp=39\u201340}}; {{harvnb|Pelras|1996|p=142}}).}} As La Maddaremmeng refused to compensate for the goods seized in P\u00e9n\u00e9ki, Wajoq and Bon\u00e9 went to war against each other.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}} Gowa and Sopp\u00e9ng sided with Wajoq in this conflict, and the joint forces succeeded in [[Battle of Passemp\u00e9|defeating Bon\u00e9 in October 1643]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=39\u201340}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=142}} Bon\u00e9 was harshly punished by being made a vassal of Gowa,{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=29}} with a Bugis noble installed as a [[regent]] responsible to a Makassar lord. A subsequent rebellion led by La Maddaremmeng's brother was also quashed, and Bon\u00e9's status was further degraded to that of a \"slave\" (i.e. a colony), while its nobles were forcibly relocated to Gowa.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=41\u201342}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=142\u2013143}} Several contested territories held by Bon\u00e9 were given to Wajoq, and a large number of people from Bon\u00e9 were forced into [[Corv\u00e9e|unpaid labor]] in Wajoq.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=29\u201330}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=42\u201343}} This humiliation entrenched a feeling of resentment among the people of Bon\u00e9 towards both Gowa and Wajoq.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=30}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=43}}\n\n=== Makassar War and Wajorese migrations (1660\u20131730) ===\nBy the second quarter of the 17th century, Gowa and Talloq had became the most politically and economically powerful polities in eastern Indonesia. The twin kingdoms' attempt to retain their hegemony brought them to a conflict with the [[Dutch East India Company]] (VOC), which wanted to monopolize the [[spice trade]] in the [[Moluccas]].{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=30}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=45\u201347}} In 1660, the Dutch attacked Gowa and managed to seize the fort of Paqnakkukang.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=49}} Gowa then forced its vassals to provide labor to build military constructions in anticipation of further conflict, which ultimately resulted in a rebellion led by the Bon\u00e9 noble [[Arung Palakka]].{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=50\u201352}} However, his attempt to revive the ''Tellumpocco'' alliance failed, as Wajoq refused to break its treaty with Gowa to join forces with the rebels.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=30}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=54}}<!-- According to the historian [[Leonard Andaya]], Wajoq's decision can be explained by the fact that its recent experiences with Gowa were much more positive than those with Bon\u00e9.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=54\u201355}} In the most recent memory of the Wajorese, it was Bon\u00e9, not Gowa, which invaded their country. Wajoq and Bon\u00e9 also had frequent disputes over territorial boundaries and the allegiance of their vassals.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=54\u201355}}{{efn|system of vassals...}} On the other hand, Wajoq's relationship with Gowa had been more friendly in the preceding years; Wajoq was one of Gowa's most trusted vassals, with the ''arung matoa'' [[La Tenrilai To Senngeng]] (r. 1658\u20131670) had even been married to a daughter of Gowa ruler [[Hasanuddin of Gowa|Hasanuddin]] (r. 1653\u20131669).{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37, 54\u201355}}--> Lacking enough support, the rebellion was successfully quelled by Gowa and Wajoq forces, driving Arung Palakka to escape to [[Buton]], and later, to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]], seeking aid from the VOC.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=56\u201359, 66}}\n\nDuring the [[Makassar War]] (1666\u20131669), Wajoq fiercely supported Gowa against the alliance of the VOC and local forces from Bon\u00e9 and elsewhere led by Arung Palakka. Even after the fall of Gowa's court Sombaopu and the formal surrender of Gowa and Talloq, the ''arung matoa'' [[La Tenrilai To Sengngeng]] (r. 1658\u20131670) still refused to abide by the [[Treaty of Bungaya]] and continued to resist the Dutch and Bon\u00e9 forces.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=31\u201332}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=37, 124\u2013126, 138}} By mid-1670, Arung Palakka had launched a large-scale invasion of Wajoq.<!-- Along the way, several Wajoq's vassals deserted and joined Bon\u00e9 forces, bringing the total number of invading forces to around 40,000 people when it arrived to besiege Tosora, the walled capital city of Wajoq.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=138\u2013139}}--> Despite hard resistance from Wajorese defenders, the walled capital city of Tosora fell to the Bon\u00e9-led forces in December 1670. La Tenrilai was [[killed in action]], and his successor [[La Paliliq To Malu]] (r. 1670\u20131679) was forced to sign a treaty restricting Wajorese political, trade and military powers, in addition to the Treaty of Bungaya.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=33\u201335}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=140\u2013141}} In spite of Wajoq's surrender, it still faced harsh retribution from Arung Palakka and the people of Bon\u00e9. Many Wajorese were kidnapped and harassed or had their belongings seized.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=36}} Bon\u00e9 also annexed the coastal territories near the mouth of [[Walanae River|Cenrana River]], which was Wajoq's sole acess to the sea.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=143}} Wajoq's complains to the Dutch at Makassar regarding Bon\u00e9's arbitrary actions were given little attention. By this time, Arung Palakka had been sending soldiers to help the VOC in [[Trunajaya rebellion|a campaign in Java]], and the VOC did not want to risk severing their relationship with an important ally.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=37\u201338}}{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|pp=142\u2013143, 190\u2013192, 205}}\n\nIt was these difficulties faced by the Wajorese in their homeland which prompted them to emigrate elsewhere.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=143}} While migration had always been an important part of Wajorese culture, it was particularly prominent in the aftermath of the Makassar War, when a large number of Wajorese migrants established themselves abroad in Makassar, eastern [[Borneo]], the [[Lesser Sunda Islands]], and the [[Straits of Malacca]] area, among other places.{{sfnp|Andaya|1981|p=143}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=38, 82}}{{sfnp|Lineton|1975b|p=178}} These diaspora communities were connected to their homeland as well as to each other by familial, commercial, political and legal ties.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82}} By the early 18th century, a sequence of Wajorese rulers had began to take advantage of these connections to revitalize their country. Several rulers ordered their people abroad to buy weapons to rearm Wajoq.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82}}{{sfnp|Duli|2010|pp=144\u2013145}} Attention was also given to commerce; one particular ''arung matoa'', [[La Tenriwerrung Puanna Sangngaji]] (r. 1711\u20131713), even proclaimed it as a moral duty, noting that the people of Wajoq \"could not 'stand upright' unless they sought riches\".{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82}} His successor, [[La Sal\u00e9wangeng To Tenrirua]] (r. 1713\u20131736), actively supported international commerce in more practical ways.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=82\u201383}} He dredged the river that leads to the capital Tosora to ease access for large boats, strengthened local industries by requiring them to appoint political representatives known as ''akkajenangngeng'', created an official governmental post with the specific role of promoting trade, and set up a fund which can be used for investment on commerce and agriculture as well as for social security purposes.{{sfnp|Duli|2010|pp=144\u2013145}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=82\u201383}}\n\n=== Wajoq under La Maddukelleng (1730\u20131754) ===\n{{sect-stub|date=April 2020}}\nSince Arung Palakka's death in 1696, none of his successor was as capable as him in maintaining Bon\u00e9's hegemony over South Sulawesi. This allowed Wajorese trade to flourish without much restriction.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=30, 69}} Interaction between Wajorese diaspora communities and their homeland intensified, and it culminated in the 1730s when the exiled Wajorese [[La Maddukelleng]] came back to South Sulawesi.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=137}} At first, he and his followers raided several communities in the western part of the peninsula and in the islands near Makassar.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=55}} In 1736, he assumed the leadership of P\u00e9n\u00e9ki (a constituent polity of Wajoq) and got involved in a confrontation with Bon\u00e9. Following a retaliatory invasion from Bon\u00e9, many Wajorese people came to support La Maddukelleng, and he assumed the position of ''arung matoa'' (r. 1736\u20131754{{efn|{{harvtxt|Noorduyn|1972|p=61}} dates his reign to 1737\u20131754, but according to {{harvtxt|Abidin|1985|p=577}} and {{harvtxt|Wellen|2014|p=145}}, he was appointed as the ''arung matoa'' of Wajoq on November 6, 1736. Wajorese sources recount that La Maddukelleng was chosen to replace La Sal\u00e9wangeng (who is reported to have voluntarily resigned), although several contemporary records indicated that he assumed the position through usurpation ({{harvnb|Wellen|2018|p=56}}).}}) not long after.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=56}} With popular support, he led Wajoq into victory over Bon\u00e9.{{sfnp|Noorduyn|1972|p=61}} By mid-1737 a peace agreement had been signed, and Bon\u00e9 was obliged to compensate for all the losses Wajoq had suffered under the rulers of Bon\u00e9 since the Makassar War.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=57}} Liberated from Bon\u00e9 dominance, Wajoq assumed a hegemonic position in South Sulawesi,{{sfnp|Noorduyn|1972|p=61}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=137, 158\u2013159}} with Wajorese record even stating that Wajoq was recognized as the leader of the ''Tellumpocco'' at the time.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=57}}\n<!--\nThe change in the balance of power in South Sulawesi concerned the Dutch, since Bon\u00e9 was their only ally in the region. La Maddukelleng attacked Dutch... retaliation...\n\n===1754\u20131957===\n\n-  19th century... expedition in South Sulawesi early 20th century... constitutionally made part of Indonesia in the late 50s.\n-->\n==Government and politics==\n{| class=\"me collapsible\" width=\"300\" style=\"float: right; clear: right; margin: 0 0 1em 1em; font-family: arial; font-size: 90%; border: 1px solid #cccccc\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: #e7dcc3\" | List of rulers{{efn|Adapted from {{harvtxt|Abidin|1985|pp=574\u2013578}}. Dates of reign for the first three rulers are not specified.}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: #99CCCC\" | ''Batara'' of Wajoq\n|-\n| La Tenribali\n|\n|-\n| La Mataesso\n|\n|-\n| La Pateddungi To Samallangiq\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: #99CCCC\" | ''Arung Matoa'' of Wajoq\n|-\n| La Pal\u00e9wo To Palippu\n| (1474\u20131481)\n|-\n| La Obbi Settiriwareq\n| (1481\u20131486)\n|-\n| La Tenritumpuq To Langiq\n| (1486\u20131481)\n|-\n| La Tadampareq Puang ri Maggalatung\n| (1491\u20131521)\n|-\n| La Tenripakado To Namp\u00e9\n| (1524\u20131535)\n|-\n| La Temassong\u00e9\n| (1535\u20131538)\n|-\n| La Warani To Temmagiang\n| (1538\u20131547)\n|-\n| La Mallageni\n| (1547)\n|-\n| La Mappapuli To Appademmeng\n| (1547\u20131564)\n|-\n| La Pakoko To Pabb\u00e9leq\n| (1564\u20131567)\n|-\n| La Mungkaceq To Uddamang\n| (1567\u20131607)\n|-\n| La Sangkuru Patauq Mulajaji\n| (1607\u20131610)\n|-\n| La Mappepulu To Appamol\u00e9\n| (1612\u20131616)\n|-\n| La Samal\u00e9wa To Appakiung\n| (1616\u20131621)\n|-\n| La Pakallongi To Alinrungi\n| (1621\u20131626)\n|-\n| To Mappassaungng\u00e9\n| (1627\u20131628)\n|-\n| La Pakallongi To Alinrungi\n| (1628\u20131636)\n|-\n| La Tenrilai To Uddamang\n| (1636\u20131639)\n|-\n| La Sigajang To Bunne\n| (1639\u20131643)\n|-\n| La Makkaraka To Patemmui\n| (1643\u20131648)\n|-\n| La Temmassongeq Puanna Da\u00e9li\n| (1648\u20131651)\n|-\n| La Parammaq To R\u00e9wo\n| (1651\u20131658)\n|-\n| La Tenrilai To Sengngeng\n| (1658\u20131670)\n|-\n| La Paliliq To Malu\n| (1670\u20131679)\n|-\n| La Pariusi Da\u00e9ng Manyampaq\n| (1679\u20131699)\n|-\n| La Tenrisessu To Timo\u00e9\n| (1699\u20131702)\n|-\n| La Mattoneq To Sakkeq\n| (1702\u20131703)\n|-\n| La Galigo To Sunia\n| (1703\u20131712)\n|-\n| La Tenriwerrung Puanna Sangngaji\n| (1712\u20131715)\n|-\n| La Sal\u00e9wangeng To Tenrirua\n| (1715\u20131736)\n|-\n| La Maddukelleng\n| (1736\u20131754)\n|-\n| La Maddanaca\n| (1754\u20131755)\n|-\n| La Passaung Puanna La Omoq\n| (1758\u20131761)\n|-\n| La Mappajung Puanna Salowo\n| (1761\u20131767)\n|-\n| La Malliungeng To All\u00e9ong\n| (1767\u20131770)\n|-\n| La Mallalengeng\n| (1795\u20131817)\n|-\n| La Manang To Appamadeng\n| (1821\u20131825)\n|-\n| La Paddengngeng Puanna Pallaguna\n| (1839\u20131845)\n|-\n| La Pawellangi Pajump\u00e9ro\u00e9\n| (1854\u20131859)\n|-\n| La Cincing Akil Ali\n| (1859\u20131885)\n|-\n| La Koro\n| (1885\u20131891)\n|-\n| La Passamulaq\n| (1892\u20131897)\n|-\n| Ishak Manggabarani\n| (1900\u20131916)\n|-\n| La Tenrioddang\n| (1926\u20131933)\n|-\n| Andiq Mangkonaq\n| (1933\u20131949)\n|}\n\nAs with many other Bugis states, Wajoq was a confederation of smaller political and territorial communities. These communities were related to each other as well as to the central government at Tosora in various ways, ranging from vassalage to alliance \"as between brothers\".{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=176\u2013177}} The polity of Wajoq was divided into three ''limpo'' or main districts, namely B\u00e9tt\u00e9mpola, Tua, and Talotenreng, which represented its three original founding communities.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|pp=49\u201350}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|pp=177\u2013178}} Each ''limpo'' held power over several smaller communities that either chose to affiliate themselves with the said ''limpo'' or were conquered.{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=50}} Each of these communities had considerable freedom, with its own leader and customs. It can also switch allegiance between different states, and by doing so, both its people and its territory will be subject to the new state.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=22}}\n\nThe paramount ruler of Wajoq was titled ''arung matoa''.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=23}} In running the day-to-day administration of Wajoq, the ''arung matoa'' was assisted by three pairs of civilian and military leaders, each pair representing one of the three ''limpo''.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=482}}{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=245}} The civilian leader of a ''limpo'' was called a ''ranreng'' or regent, while the military leader was called a ''bat\u00e9 lompo'' or \"standard bearer\".{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=178}} The titles of the ''bat\u00e9 lompo'' were taken from the banner they carried: ''Pilla'' or \"Scarlet\" for B\u00e9tt\u00e9mpola, ''Patola'' or \"Multi-colored\" for Talotenreng, and ''Cakkuridi'' or \"Yellow\" for Tua.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=23}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=485}} Each of the ''ranreng'' and  ''bat\u00e9 lompo'' were at least as powerful as the ''arung matoa''; together, these seven officials formed the state's highest governing body, known as ''Petta Wajoq''.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=23}}{{sfnp|Pelras|1996|p=178}}\n\nThe ''arung matoa'' was chosen among the \"white-blood\" or nobility class. The position of arung matoa cannot be held at once with another office. It also cannot be inherited and can only be held for life as long as the ruler was deemed fit for the position.{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|pp=465, 535}} A ruler in precolonial South Sulawesi was expected to be subordinate to the state and the ''[[adat]]'' or customary law which delineates the autonomy of local communities; failure to do so may result in removal from office. The ''arung matoa'' La Samal\u00e9wa To Appakiung (r. 1612\u20131616), for example, was deposed by his people, reportedly because of his arbitrary actions.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=22}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|p=385}}\n\nThe central governing council of Wajoq consisted of 40 officials, collectively called the ''Arung Patampulu'' (lit. \"Forty Lords\"{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=165}}), of which the ''arung matoa'' was a member as well as the head.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=482}} The whole members only convened on certain occasions, including the election of a new ''arung matoa''.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=23, 175}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2018|p=51}} The power of ''Arung Patampulu'', in turn, was balanced by three non-noble officials known as ''punggawa'', who were elected among the elders of each district.{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=482}}{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=245}} These ''punggawa'' had considerable power. According to Brooke:{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=245}}\n\n{{quote\n|text=The powers of these pangawas [sic], or tribunes of the people, is considerable. With them only it rests to summon a meeting of the council of forty. They possess the right of veto to the appointment of an aru matoah [sic]. Their command alone is a legal summons to war, no chief or body having right, or even authority, to call the freemen to the field.\n|author=James Brooke\n}}\n\nIn addition to having ''punggawa'' as the formal permanent representation in the government, \"respectable\" commoners and village heads were also entitled to participate in the occasional extraordinary deliberative assembly which might be held in case the ''Arung Patampulu'' could not agree on the best way to resolve certain issues. These commoners may discuss and give input to the government on the best way to resolve these issues, although the ultimate decision in this kind of situations rested in the hands of ''arung matoa''.{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=246}}\n<!--\n- Diaspora governmental structure (focus on Borneo and Makassar)...\n-->\n\n==Culture and society==\n{{see also|Bugis people}}\n{{sect-stub|date=April 2020}}\nWajorese texts often reiterate that \"the people of Wajoq are free\", and that their only master is the customary law, which is based on consensus. The concept of the \"freedoms of Wajoq\" included, among others: [[freedom of speech|freedom of expressing opinions]], freedom to act based on one's intention, [[freedom of movement]], [[freedom of contract]], and the freedom from unjust punishment.{{sfnp|Reid|1998|p=148}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1983|p=481}}{{sfnp|Abidin|1985|pp=433, 447\u2013448}} These \"freedoms\", however, had limitations and do not necessarily apply to the whole population.\n\nBugis women in the precolonial states of South Sulawesi were routinely involved in many aspects of the society. Women were also actively involved in the government. One 19th-century observer states that the women of South Sulawesi were commonly \"consulted by the men on all public affairs\" and were often \"raised to the throne, [even] when the monarchy is elective\".{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=250}} The British adventurer [[James Brooke]] (future [[Rajah of Sarawak]]), notes that at the time of his visit to Wajoq in 1840, four out of six members of Petta Ennengng\u00e9 were women, who frequently \"appear in public like the men; ride, rule, and visit even foreigners, without the knowledge or consent of their husbands.\"{{sfnp|Henley|Caldwell|2019|p=250}}\n\n==Economy==\nWajoq was the source of most South Sulawesi overseas merchants between late 17th and late 19th centuries.{{sfnp|Reid|1998|p=147}} Wajorese commerce extended as far as [[Sumatra]], [[Cambodia]], and [[New Guinea]].{{sfnp|Lineton|1975b|p=178}}{{sfnp|Reid|1998|p=147}} Throughout the Maritime Southeast Asia, Wajorese and other Bugis merchants acted as intermediaries between large and small trading nations.{{sfnp|Lineton|1975b|p=178}} Wajorese trade flourished in part because of deliberate support from the government at Wajoq as well as from Wajorese communities abroad.{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=67\u201368}} Leaders of Wajorese overseas communities regularly convened to advance their interest. One such conference in the early 18th century saw the codification of laws regulating Wajorese commerce and navigation, popularly called the Ammana Gappa's law code, after the then leader of the Wajorese community in Makassar. These laws set up frameworks for managing credit and debts as well as regulating other kinds of business relationships, providing ways to resolve conflict and giving Wajorese merchants advantages over merchants from other groups in Maritime Southeast Asia.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|pp=84, 91, 97}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|pp=64\u201365, 71}} Such a law code, according to historian Kathryn Wellen, is \"highly unusual, if not unique, for early modern insular Southeast Asia\".{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=84}}\n\nThe government financially supported Wajorese merchants by providing monetary loans, taken from the fund established by La Sal\u00e9wangeng. Borrowers were obliged to return the principals alongside parts of their profits. The profits would then be used to further Wajoq's interest, such as building armaments or renovating the state's mosque. This system allowed a large segment of Wajorese population to participate in commerce while also utilizing their economic power for the benefit of the society as a whole.{{sfnp|Wellen|2009|p=82\u201383, 97}}{{sfnp|Wellen|2014|p=76}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Early history of Gowa and Talloq]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|indent=yes|30em}}\n: {{cite journal |last=Abidin |first=Andi Zainal |year=1983 |tit